Carl is a 2 year old, 75# Staffie mix. He needs a very special owner who is willing to work him through some behavior issues. He likes some other dogs but is not recommended for homes with children.  Carl struggles with feeling safe and comfortable in his environment.  He will need in home training and behavior work to help him overcome his anxiety as he has acted out when overly excited. 

If you'd like more information on Carl our behavior manager would be happy to answer any questions you may have.  After that we could set up a series of meetings to introduce you to this beautiful boy.

If you are interested in meeting any of our adoptable dogs, please fill out an application at https://www.mlar.org/adoption-overview

E-mails regarding adoption are not considered an application. 

Out-of-state applicants (outside PA/NJ/DE) will not be considered, unless there are special circumstances. 

Please visit our web site for more detailed information on the animals in our care, our educational campaigns, and for helpful tips on adoption.  www.MLAR.org

animal.description:
Marty is an adorable and shy 6 month old.  He weighs about 25 lbs and is very sweet.  He likes to play and do all puppy things, but may need a few minutes to get past his initial shyness with new people. Marty feels most comfortable in the company of other welcoming and playful dog(s). Marty needs a family that will love him, teach him new things (like the stairs), socialize him with other friendly pups, give cuddles when it's time for bed, and help him grow into a confident dog. 

Here at NMAR, we don't just find good homes for our dogs, we find the the specific good home for each specific dog. While we work toward those matches, our dogs are safe and happy in foster homes, or in our home-like shelter, where they have the chance to learn some life skills and show us what they need to be happy and healthy.

REQUIREMENTS:  Marty needs a home with a fenced yard and another playful, confident dog that will show him the ropes.  Kids should be older than 10 years due to his shyness.

Adoption fee is $225 and includes: spay/neuter, parvo/distemper series of shots, rabies (if dog is old enough), bordetella, heartworm preventative while here, worming, and microchip. 

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting Marty, please visit our website and fill out an adoption application: www.northmeckanimalrescue.org

animal.description:
FOSTER UPDATE:

PETIE! Its safe to say that Petie takes two things very seriously in life, relaxing and babysiting. Petie has been in foster for a little over a week now and has truly shown us how wonderful he is. He is great in the home and will be a wonderful family addition. He needs to be the only dog and he does suffer from chronic allergies that his new family will need to work with their vet to manage. Dont let this sweet senior slip through your fingers!

PETIE - 9 1/2 years old, 70 pounds, house trained, good with kids and cats, no other dogs, friendly, happy, excited on the leash, loves to walk, loves to play, sits on command, loves treats, pulls on the leash.

PETIE is that dog. You know, the one who makes you smile from the start. He's happy and he himself has a perpetual smile on his face. Nothing gets him down. He's excited to meet you and excited to go outside. He pulls on the leash... in that excitement... consider yourself forewarned! He was raised with small children but this doesn't mean he should be left unsupervised with new children in the beginning. Letting new dogs get settled in a new home is important as the dog gets used to everything and you get used to him. PETIE is good with cats but remember, your cat is new to him so slow introductions will be so beneficial for all. PETIE is already house trained and very experienced in a home. He has always been left free roaming in the home when the owners went out without issue. Petie is accepting appointments now! Call the Virginia Beach Animal Care and Adoption Center at 385-4444 or go to our Facebook page and make an appointment to meet him. We're open daily except for Tuesday's. Thank you for choosing adoption!

animal.description:
Sparkle was adopted through K9O as a puppy and was recently returned to us. As she matured it turned out that she was not a good fit for her adoptive family. She is now 1.5 years old and doing very well in her foster home. She is athletic and loves walks, but also enjoys a good nap and snuggle session.

Sparkle can be picky about her people and is sometimes nervous around new friends. She prefers a calm energy and would do best in a quiet home without small children. She gets along with other dogs but takes time to warm up and does not like to share, so she should be the only dog in the home or under the care of humans who understand how to manage resource guarding behaviors. She has not been cat tested at this time.

Sparkle would love a fenced yard to run in! She is 100% potty trained and is very well-behaved. She had a chance to prove herself recently, spending the whole day with free run of the house and she did not get into any trouble! She is a very good girl and deserves a very good home.

If you are interested in adopting Sparkle, please submit the application at k9orphans.org to be considered.

animal.description:
Cassi...this poor girl has been through so much already...

Cassi was encountered by a good samaritan who was out riding his bike. He saw her lying next to the bike path and she appeared to be suffering or dying. He was not able to get close to her so he reached out to rescues and posted on social media until we answered his plea.


Like so many other dogs living in the woods, along with our bayous, or on the streets, Cassi was starving and terrified. The heat had become unbearable for her, especially without any water or shelter. She was evaluated at Vergi an emergency vet who gave her fluids and monitored her overnight. She was able to go to our usual vet where she received her vaccines and was given the okay to go into a home to gain weight to be healthy enough to be spayed. She unfortunately is heartworm positive and HAS COMPLETED HEARTWORM TREATMENT ALREADY. Cassi was very scared of people when she was first rescued. We brought her to a boarding/training facility for the staff to help socialize her.


Since she has been there, she has absolutely blossomed with people and she is great with other dogs. She has gained weight and she is more than ready for a home of her own! Cassi is clean in her kennel, great on  a leash, and pretty laid back in general.


The vet believes she is about 3 years old and she weighs 60 lbs. Cassi is now spayed, up to date on vaccines, and has completed heartworm treatment.


Email us at info@adorehouston.org if you have questions about Cassi!

animal.description:
Sanctuary update: Shadow is looking for an adult only home that is very active and well versed in training. He has issues with resource guarding and is fence reactive to the point that he will "zone out" and forget that the person on the other side is a friend. He has great potential, but this is a dog that wants a job, activity and training! He has taken his resource guarding to the point that he has actually bitten people and other dogs. He needs an outlet for his energy and the right person to work on his behavioral issues. He is very food motivated and we have been working to teach him to sit and wait for his bowl, and to eat once he has been told to "get it". Shadow loves and craves attention and affection. If you have a predictable, adult only home and feel that you are willing and able to give Shadow what he needs to be a happy and content companion, please email us at sanctuary@milofoundation.org

Past Notes: His main issues are resource guarding and high drive. He is very ball motivated, He is a great swimmer and it is serves as a great anxiety reducer for him. He will charge off and should be on a long line. He does return. He is a natural hunter and needs extensive training for his behavior issues. Someone with patience and understanding. I truly love him.

animal.description:
Kingston is a handsome 7-year old male Pit Bull Terrier who arrived at the HSOV on September 21, 2020 after he was picked up in the Cutler Ohio area by the Washington County Dog Warden (and was surrendered by his owner).

Kingston has a brown short smooth coat with a large patch of white on his chest, a long tail, and an adorable face with a splash of white on his muzzle/white stripe on his forehead, a liver-colored nose, and short cropped ears. Kingston was quite friendly when HSOV Kennel tech Kim Cowman accompanied him outdoors for his photo session when these photos were taken on September 22, 2020 :)

The information on Kingston's intake form indicates that he is not good other animals. He apparently was kept indoors since it is noted that Kingston is housebroken.

Kingston weighs 55 lbs and walks fairly well on a leash.

Kingston was neutered on September 30, 2020 and was also given rabies vaccine. Kingston was adopted later that afternoon.

UPDATE: We were saddened when Kingston was returned to our shelter on January 7, 2021. His adopter stated that Kingston did not get along with her other dog. 

Kingston appears to have some arthritis (or neurological issues) in his hind legs and hips and also has a slight head tilt these days :( We are listing him as a 'Special Needs Dog' for that reason but we prefer to think of him as merely very special.  Kingston still loves to walk with our kennel techs and volunteers and puts forth a noble effort whenever anyone offers him the opportunity for some one-on-one time and attention :)

So this sweet boy is looking for a fabulous home with a compassionate individual or family who will love and cherish him forever and ever.

animal.description:
MEET CANNON !!!

This boy is just amazing with both big and small dogs, but is a rough and rowdy player. Cannon would do great with another like minded dog with a big fenced yard to play. Because of his rowdiness, please consider a slow introduction to other family dogs. Cannon is doggie door trained and doesn't mind being crated while you are away from home. This sweet boy is still a pup and demonstrates lots of typical puppy behavior--occasional digging, mouthy and jumpy when excited. He may be too rough for young children. And keep flip flops, couch pillows and other fun items out of reach! Cannon likes to take them outside and eat them. Also, some other favorites include rope toys for tug of war, chew toys, tennis balls and bones. Kongs with peanut butter are the best and will make him happily go in his kennel.

Cannon also enjoys walks and would be a great hiking partner. He is still working on his leash manners and does like to pull. He is a bit car shy but once in, he settles down quickly and is very well behaved. Although Cannon is a great sleeper at night, but he is a early riser and ready to play! This friendly boy likes everyone he meets--he just loves attention. Cannon could use some basic training but he is intelligent and eager to please and will learn very quickly. Won't you give Cannon a chance? He has a lot of potential and can't wait for you to make him part of your family.

If you are interested in meeting this dog, please visit our website for our online application www.underdogaz.com

animal.description:
Meet Dozer!

animal.description:
Meet Teddy!!
Shih Tzu
(DOB: 09/04/2010)

Teddy was turned into the Wayne County Shelter because he was “too old, blind and had no quality of life”. He’s about 10 years old and weighs just 14 lbs. 

We took him to Berkeley Veterinary Clinic to have him evaluated. Teddy’s blood work is fine. He's amazingly heartworm negative and now groomed and neutered. 

Teddy is blind because of dry eye which was never treated. Other than that, he's a healthy, loving, happy little guy! And house-trained! Because of his blindness, he can become a little anxious if he can't find his way out of rooms. Teddy loves to be near the sound of his foster mom’s voice and he follows her voice by command. Teddy walks fine on leash. He is very laid back with no running or jumping.

Teddy enjoys exploring around the house and in the yard, but he needs to be closely monitored. Teddy has special needs which include blindness in both eyes and possibly some skin allergies. His skin is improving with treatment. (Teddy will likely need lubricant drops for his dry eyes daily for the rest of his life).

Teddy loves snacks and puppy massages. The company of other dogs and cats do not bother him. When foster mom leaves Teddy alone, she leaves him confined to an area of the house or his puppy pen to ensure his safety and comfort. He is happy snuggled in his bed and blanket.

Teddy is up-to-date on vaccines, neutered, microchipped and being maintained on monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention.

Teddy will need a home that has experience with blind dogs. He also needs a loving and calm environment. He still has good years left to give his person lots of LOVE. Thanks to Berkeley Veterinary Clinic and Cuts-4-Muttz for helping this sweet senior boy!

Message from foster mom: It has been a joy to foster Teddy. He is the sweetest little guy and no trouble at all. Senior dogs are the best!

This dog is currently being fostered as part of Diamonds in the Ruff Canine Rescue. An application is required, along with a home visit and small adoption fee.  Applicants must be at least 21 years of age. **FENCED IN YARD REQUIRED**

Please visit us on our Facebook page for additional photos, give us a like while you're there! 
https://www.facebook.com/diamondsintheruffNC

All of our dogs are fostered in homes and are INDOOR dogs. We believe all dogs are family members and should be treated as valued members of the household. 

Please review our adoption guidelines for further information on adopting from Diamonds in the Ruff Canine Rescue before submitting an application. www.DITRnc.com.


.

animal.description:
Breed: German Shepherd
Sex: Neutered Male
DOB: ~09/07/2018
Weight: 70 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Timid but Curious, Quiet, Sweet, Energetic
History: Transferred from another shelter/puppy mill seizure
Good With: Dogs
Fence Requirements: Physical fence required. 
Ideal Home: Dog-experienced home. No young children (teenagers ok).
Special Info: Remi is discovering his love for tennis balls!

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***


Hello world!!!
 

My name is Kane and I am the most handsome, lickey lickey boy there is and now I am ready to find my forever home! Living with foster mom has been great and all and she has really gone the distance to help prepare me for my forever home. You see, when I first came into her care I was such a nervous, fearful dude that I really only liked her and a very select few people. Men in particular scared me and I wanted to make sure that new people left me alone so I used my big, scary voice to keep people away. 

Foster mom didn't completely lose hope with me though and she sent me to meet a new friend who does this thing called ""training"". I'm not sure what training is exactly but I will tell you this, I really got to start seeing the world with my friend Dawn. We went to parks for nice walks (plus the car rides!), and even got to go to restaurants together! She really expanded my world. And with that expansion I started to learn that people really aren't so scary. 

After ""training"" I got to come home to foster mom and boy was that exciting! Unfortunately I broke with some nasty skin allergies that required going to the vet and foster mom was not sure how I was going to do at first. Well let me tell you this, I made a lot more new friends! And now when I go to see them I whine and want to say hello and lickey lickey them until they just can't stand it anymore! And now that all my skin allergies are under control (I just take a pill with my food twice a day to help curb the itch) I am all ready to find my forever home. 

Could that be you? Here are some things I am looking for:

I am looking for a home where I have a mom/dad who is a leader. I need someone to love me who will also let me know that they have things under control and I am just along for the ride. The more confident my person is, the more confident I am, funny how that works right? My mom/dad needs to understand that I am not a dog who needs to meet all their friends right away. I need some time to work up to meeting new people and knowing that they are okay and we can be friends! I am okay with having to be put away when new people are at the house.

I am looking for a home where there are no small kids. While I have been around foster mom's kids, the energy is just not something I really enjoy. Plus, I am still learning impulse control. Foster mom says I like to ""mouth her"" sometimes when I am doing all my kisses and while she also says I have a ""soft"" mouth, it is something kids would not appreciate. 

I would also prefer to be the only furry love of your life. I made some doggy friends while at training but overall I am just happier being your only love and cats are just way too tempting to chase. They look like squirrels and I can't help but want to chase them.

I am perfectly housebroken, even when I had to take some prednisone for my skin. I am also kennel trained. A fenced in yard would be cool to have so that I can run and play off leash safely. I really do enjoy time outside and getting to just dog around the yard. 

But even though I would love a fenced in yard, I still want a home that likes to walk and be active. You see, after going to training, I really really enjoy going for walks and getting to explore the world around me. Plus, the more I am out in the world the more confidence I have in being a part of it. Foster mom will happily help teach my new family how to walk me to where I feel safe and am such a good boy. 

I know I keep mentioning this training thing, but I also figured it was worth mentioning that my friend Dawn said she would be happy to work with whomever becomes my forever family too! Plus I can't lie, I always enjoy seeing old friends! 

Now for all the nitty gritty details: I am neutered, up to date on vaccinations, dewormed, on heartworm and flea/tick prevention, and microchipped. My adoption fee is $300 which includes the professional training I went through! If you have questions about me you can email my foster mom at jones@secondchancenc.org

animal.description:
This super happy-go-lucky girl is 6 year-old September.  September arrived at the shelter as a stray on 9/3/2020, but is safe with us now.   When she arrived at the shelter as a stray, she was terrified and depressed, preferring to lay in a corner of her stall and avoid anyone who tried to get her attention.  Over time, though, shelter staff earned her trust and saw a much happier, confident pup!  

She still has a ways to go and she seems to be more nervous of men than women but, considering her transformation while stuck at the shelter, we’re confident that once she’s in a loving home, she’ll come around very quickly!  In fact, she has settled in quite nicely with her foster family!  While September can live with other dogs and has done great with other dogs at the shelter, it would require an experienced family that can recognize and manage the external stimuli that can get September excited.  Otherwise, would be best for her to be the only dog.

September has spent two weeks with professional trainers and they have said she is super sweet and one of their favorites.  They did not observe any adverse reactions towards people and was super sweet with everyone she interacted with.  

She loves to play fetch and will drop the toy at your feet when the command “out” is given.  She is also doing well with other commands such as sit, stay, come, kennel, etc.  Additionally, she is crate-trained as well.  However, her absolute favorite thing to do is cuddle!  She loves snuggling up to any human nearby and if there is any little space for her to squish any closer to you, she will take the opportunity.


Please help us get sweet September into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!
 
If you would like to adopt loving September, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

animal.description:
Keller is an aprox 2yr old deaf pittie who was found roaming the streets in Owensboro and was picked up by animal control. While in their shelter he was a handful to say the least. Since coming to ARC, staff has been working on teaching Keller how to "communicate" using basic hand signs. This has also been a learning experience for us as well. Keller has shown us that he is a very intelligent dog. He has learned to "sit" and is slowly learning signs for "off" and "wait". Keller does very well with other dogs at ARC and is currently best buds with Hank. Keller has learned how to play well with others by watching how other dogs respond to himself as well as people.
Keller walks well on a harness but is easily distracted by the sights around him and we are still learning ways to keeping him focused on the task at hand.
Keller is a very happy guy and is so eager to please. He is very treat motivated. Keller would thrive with having training from a professional or just someone who can do one on one with him. 
Above all, he is a really great dog with personality that goes for miles. He's always happy! Keller would do best with a dog of his own energy level and one that doesn't show dominance over him. Keller and Hank  are both relatively couch potatoes after a good game of tug. He will do best in a home with older children. Best with no cats. He really needs someone who can take the time and have the patience with helping him learn to make the best of his silent world.

animal.description:
Zulu is an affectionate rambunctious pitbull mix. He is around 57lbs and a year and a half old, but has to spirit of a big puppy.  He’s the type of dog that lives in the moment. Zulu has a very curious personality so we are looking for an adopter who can keep a mindful eye and give lots of structure. 

Zulu loves everyone he meets! He wags his tail nonstop when someone gives him a glance. Due to his powerful wiggles and excitement, we’re recommending him to an adult only home. Zulu is housebroken and crate trained (even though he will complain a bit). He knows sit, down, shake, and is working on muzzle training. To make sure Zulu has the best chances, his foster parents have been working with a trainer on leash skills, reactivity, and place command. Zulu should be an only dog, but can work up to a structured pack walk for healthy socialization. He would do best in a quiet suburban neighborhood.

We are looking for a strong breed savvy adopter who loves an active dog and a silly face. His forever parents must be dedicated to maintaining and continuing his training. Zulu’s trainer has dedicated a complimentary 90 minute transition training session. If you would like to see Zulu’s foster journey, please see the highlights on his foster’s instagram @ohcowdog! 

If you are interested in Zulu, please see our criteria below before applying. 

Pit bull & strong breed adoption criteria
- Must be over 25 years of age to adopt a Pit Bull, Pit Bull mix, or strong breed dog.
- Written landlord permission or a pet policy allowing the specific breed is required for adoption approval.
- A virtual home visit may be required.
- Training or breed experience is required as part of the adoption.
- Agree to not take the dog to dog parks or dog daycare.
- Pit Bull only: our values very closely aligned with Villalobos Rescue Center. Read Pit Bull Facts on their website (https://vrcpitbull.com/pit-bull-facts/). We will not match our pit bull dogs in homes who have not done their research. 

If you are interested in meeting please fill out an application at our website www.gobeyondrescue.org/adopt. Our adoption fee is $350 and includes spay/neuter, microchipping and up to date vaccines. We Adopt in the SF Bay Area Only.

animal.description:
Apply at    http://caninehumane.org/adoption-application/

Hi! I'm Cooper! I've been at the shelter for 6 months now, I love everyone here but I really wish I had a home of my own! Everyone here tells me my loud bark is what scares people away... why don't they understand that I just want to say hi?! Being  behind a kennel door can be frustrating for an outgoing and exuberant pup like me! I am an active dog who likes playing fetch, going for runs, and for long hikes! I consider myself a package deal---I will shower my family with lots of snuggles and kisses while also keeping any strangers away from the house! So far I know sit, down, and paw! I love learning and working for food so I hope my future family will teach me more tricks! Did I say I was house trained AND crate trained?! Well, I AM! I can't wait to find my future family!

Apartments, busy households, and homes in the city will NOT be considered. Coop needs a quieter neighborhood and lots of space to get his energy out! Applicants who have not owned a large dog before will not be considered.


Adoption Fee is $350

animal.description:
The world has waited for Walter and now here he is looking for his new home!!! 
 Walter is almost 7 and he officially has a new lease on life.  Walter spent his entire life on a chain until he came to us last November.  He lived in the elements year-round with hardly no human contact and defiantly no care.  When he arrived at HCW he had received no vetting and really didn't know how interact with people.  He tested positive for heart worms, he has since completed his treatment and he is officially heart worm negative.  You could tell he had, had chronic ear issues but all of that is under control now.  He's healthy as can be now.  He is house and crate trained.  He currently lives in the house on our rescue property and he has amazing house manner (loves the heat and ac, oh and the sofa).  He's great with other dogs, he can be a little bossy when he wants attention from the humans (his bark gives it away).  I will be honest and tell you he isn't a fan of anyone poking and prodding on him, the vet does have to muzzle him.  He can sometimes be grumpy, so we are going to request a home without small children.  But I think it's just because in his 7 years he's never experienced what he has in the last year.  He's a lover and he has finally adjusted to a life of love and trust. 

If you feel like Walter has your heart please follow the link to submit an adoption application: www.hcwdogrescue.com/adoptionapplication.


*Adoption Fee*
$200.00 includes the following:  neuter, parasite free, rabies vaccination, DHLPP vaccination, Bordetella vaccination, microchip, heartworm negative and current on prevention.

Thanks for choosing adoption!!!!

animal.description:
Tootsie is a fun, sweet and lovable seven-year-old, 56-pound, tan and white female terrier-mix looking for a loving guardian. 

Tootsie rolls over for belly rubs and has a delightful personality. Her tail is always happily wagging. 

Tootsie knows the command “sit” and takes treats gently from your fingers.

She is currently being kenneled in Union, Illinois, where she is great with all the other dogs, but not cats!

Tootsie is also wonderful with people of all ages. She is very sweet, snugly and loving. She prefers cuddling to playing ball and doesn’t seem to have an interest in playing fetch.

Tootsie was found stray in Schaumburg, Illinois, and her teeth are all ground down. Perhaps she was chewing on a chain or rocks? So she recently had all the nubs removed so she only has a couple of teeth left.

I first photographed Tootsie in June of 2017 and she has been kenneled ever since.

She is crate-trained and appears to be housebroken. Isn’t it time she found the home of her dreams?

To meet and possibly adopt Tootsie, please contact Melia at melia88@comcast.net for an adoption application. 

Her adoption fee of $200 benefits the rescued dogs of Lucky Dog Rescue. She is healthy, spayed, up-to-date on vaccines, micro-chipped and heartworm-tested negative.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please Click Here to Fill Out an Online Adoption Application!
******TITUS MUST BE THE ONLY ANIMAL IN THE HOME!******
Titus is a very high-Energy and goofy boy!
He comes from a high-kill shelter in CA, and was pulled out of there just in time to save his life.
This boy deservingly ended up here in the wonderful PNW!
He just wants to play-play-play!!!
He LOVES to go on walks/hikes and LOVES his toys!!!
He is much easier to walk if you give him the first 3-5 minutes to jog!!!
He is a pretty good listener, but he gets super excited and likes to jump up so we are working on that! Need his attention ASAP?? Squeeker toys!!!
He isn't mean to people, but he can be nippy in a playful way so we wouldn't want him around younger children!
He is VERY strong, and would need a strong owner to be sure you can control him on walks ext.!
He is crate trained, loves car rides, LOVES his barista who gives him treats, and does know basic manners but he is still learning how to focus! haha
Titus was used as a bait-dog in his early years and has visible bite marks on his face and body. You can tell that someone was not very nice to him, especially when he sees a rope/leash.
Poor baby boy did NOT deserve to end his life that way, so we want him to spend the rest of his days comfortable and knowing that nobody will EVER hurt him again!!!
For that reason, animals trigger Titus, and he should not be allowed near them without a muzzle on!
We are working on positive-association to a Muzzle to that it is not seen as a punishment, rather than a safety barrier for him and for other animals on his walks and vet-trips!

Once again due to high volume of apps with other animals:
******TITUS MUST BE THE ONLY ANIMAL IN THE HOME!******
NO EXCEPTIONS!
He is not as fence/barrier reactive, and will walk past a dog on his walk with no problem unless that dog was being super invasive!
He would definitely protect you and your property from unwanted guests/critters!!!
He is pretty quiet, barely barks.
He also has a very handsome smile (not a snarl, a real smile haha)

animal.description:
MEET OLIVER!!

Are you interested in adding a 4 legged friend to your home? Oliver is a calm, super sweet and generally mellow guy, but he does not fully know his strength when playing, so it is recommended he goes to a home with no children (or older children aged 16+). Oliver is dog friendly, big dogs small dogs young dogs old dogs, he loves them all! Oliver has a 16 year old blind chihuahua foster sister who occasionally bumps into him, and he is not bothered by her at all! Dog intros are still recommended though, as per our usual recommendation. Oliver LOVES going for walks, but he is very reactive and tries to chase any cats he sees outside. It's not clear how he is with cats in a home, but based on this it is recommended he go to a home with no cats. It is possible it would be different inside a home.

Oliver has some basic training. He knows how to walk on a leash (but does still pull a moderate amount), is potty trained, uses the doggy door, knows how to sit, knows 'come here', and is crate trained. He loves to go for rides in the car as well, but only if the windows are down! He needs a committed family who will continue to work on his training. What he really likes is water and the hose. Get him a kiddy pool, and he will love you forever. Just make sure to protect the hose because he thinks it is a toy. Oliver also has the cutest stretch he does when he's tired or trying to get comfortable, it's adorable!

If you have other dogs and leave food down, he will eat it! We are working on that :) Oliver can be a little stubborn, but what he really wants most is a home to call his own where he can nap comfortably and get lots of pets. Oliver has allergies and will need ongoing treatment for this. We put 1 capsule of fish oil in his food once a day, and he gets Benadryl 2x a day and this has helped tremendously! We also give him baths with shampoo from the vet, and that is the only treatment he has received for his allergies, easy-peasy!

Oliver will need time to decompress in a new home, and an experienced owner is recommended. He needs someone to lead the pack otherwise Oliver will assume the alpha position. Over time he will realize you are his forever home, and then he can relax and enjoy the rest of his years the way he was supposed to live them--getting belly rubs, lounging in the pool, and chewing on bones.

We have been fostering Oliver through Underdog Rescue of Arizona since the end of October. While he's happy to be out of the shelter, he wants to be with his people in his furever home. Are you interested in meeting Oliver? Please reach out to Underdog Rescue of Arizona,

animal.description:
My name is Gizmo and I am a 17 pound Terrier mix thats approximately 4-5 years old. 

I am a fun energetic always on the go fun loving kinda kinda guy! I have been known to be a little shy until I get to know you.  But truly I just want to be seen played with and loved! There is no way possible I could ever get too much 1:1 attention... it’s what I crave!  I love chewing on chew toys, bones, and anything to keep me entertained as I never like to remain idle!! I love hugs .. and walks and treats! I get along well with everyone - humans, dogs, kids... and I’ve never met some I don’t love!  I love toys & I walk well on a leash...what more could you possibly want in a forever companion?!! Won’t you take me home? Let’s make 2021 our year to be a forever family

ALL adoptions require a completed application, vet check, home check and final contract.  The application to adopt can be found at www.camorescue.com.

Adoption fees are variable and includean8.25% sales tax. Up to date vaccines, microchip, spay/neuter are included in the fee.

Once your application has been approved, we will put you in touch with the foster to set up a  meet and greet. We are a foster based RESCUE, not a shelter. All of our dogs are in individual foster homes. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We select the best applicant for each dog, based on the dog's needs. 
For the safety of our small breed dogs and based on our past experiences, we will not place our dogs in homes with large breed dogs.    

CAMO rescue is a 501c3 whose primary focus is rescuing small dogs from the euthanasia list from high kill TX shelters.   
EIN # is 46-5486022
We rescue 800+ animals a year.

Follow us on Facebook at www.facebook.com/camorescue

Our donation link is http://www.paypalme/camorescue 

We are strictly volunteer based, no salaries are paid and 100% of donations go towards rescuing dogs.

animal.description:
My name is Boomer. My owners adopted me from another family in Arkansas. They loved me very much but could no longer afford to take care of me. I was underweight and had some matting that had to be cut out when I came into rescue. I am gaining weight and my coat is filling back in nicely.

I am 3 years old and such a sweet boy! I am affectionate and as you can see I love to give the Pyr paw! When people talk to me I am ready to learn and please. You can ask me to sit, down, wait, and come. I am good with children, fine with cats, and good with dogs of all sizes. I'm still playful and one of my favorite things are squeaky toys. I'm very gentle with them. When they squeak I lay them down and nuzzle them. I never have accidents in the house, I like car rides, and am good on a leash. If I hear sounds outside, I will alert you with my bark. My home needs a 6 ft fence as I am pretty agile. I will come to you neutered, up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, and up to date on heartworm and flea/tick preventatives. I have been very patient, but I am ready for a family of my own! 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved, you must also pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. Children in my home can be 8 years or older. I can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, Arkansas, and Oklahoma. My rescue is able to transport me to those states. If you would like to give me a furever home, please fill out an application on my rescue's website. 

Being fostered in Mountain Home, AR

animal.description:
Meet Teddy, he is a 3-5 year old Lab Golden Amstaff Mix. Teddy has had a rough start to life but is an incredibly happy and loving dog. 

Despite being a total lovebug once he knows you, Teddy is very protective over his home and his people causing him to bark at new people coming in who he hasn't yet met. Teddy has come a long way in his training and in addition to accepting new people after meeting them outside, he has also learned to sit  shake, and comes when he is called. 

Teddy is housebroken but due to his kidney issue he drinks a lot of water and needs to be let out more often. Teddy's forever home will be one where his people can come let him out throughout the day. 

Teddy gets along with dogs of all sizes. He and his foster brother (Mastiff) play well together and he has also played well with smaller dogs. Teddy loves going on walks and swimming, if it were up to Teddy he would go on as many long walks as possible everyday. Teddy is a very happy go lucky dog and is looking for his forever family who is willing to continue to work to make him his best self, but still love him unconditionally.  

****PLEASE READ******** 
Dogs in our program are fostered in a private home, we ask that you fill out an application prior to requesting to set up a meeting or you can meet them at an upcoming adoption clinic. 

Visit our website or FB page for dates/times. If they are still listed on Petfinder, they are still available. Due to the volume of emails we receive daily, We can not respond to "Is he/she still available" or "how can I meet them".  

Applications can be filled out here  http://rottieempirerescue.com/adopt-2/dog-adoption-application/

animal.description:
Beautiful Bella is a recruit in Operation Second Chance, also known as the Gwinnett Jaildog Program. This great program saves shelter dogs from euthanasia, placing them with inmates at the county jail who have been approved to train and nurture them so that they will be good pets in their permanent adoptive homes. The goal is for each dog to be leash trained, housebroken, and have knowledge of basic obedience commands.

Our gorgeous Bella from our Gwinnett Jail Dogs Program is still waiting for the right, loving family to find her.  She has been with the program for almost 3 years and needs a home where she is the only dog.  She is a senior girl who is approximately eight years old with some arthritis/hip issues that go along with the German Shepherd breed.  She would be a great addition for a family without small children and someone that is familiar with a working breed dog.  For more information on Bella, visit www.jaildogs.org and fill out an adoption application if you’re willing to offer her a loving retirement home.

Bella is fully vetted -- spayed, heartworm negative, and current on vaccinations and deworming.  Her adoption fee is $250 (cash only, please).

You can check the status of your application by emailing jaildogs@gmail.com. 

Get more info about the Gwinnett Jaildog Program at www.jaildogs.org.
animal.name: JAILDOG Bella

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.12/31 UPDATE: - Zane is still working with his foster mom and a trainer to work on being calmer when passing order dogs. Zane is really good at redirecting his attention and going the other direction when another dog is spotted. All the low calorie treats he gets has slowed his wight loss a little bit but he is still down 10 pounds from entering the rescue.
I am potty trained, and my foster mom leaves me out all day with no issue. I have a crate that I hang out in every now and then, but I would prefer to be in your personal space if you are home. When I am home alone, I mostly lay on the couch and bark at people outside or sleep right on my mommy's pillow's. I do not surf the countertops but one time I did eat an entire gingerbread house that mommy left on the table way to close to the edge. It was practically calling for me to eat it!
Even though I am reactive when seeing other dogs, I love ALL HUMANS from little kids to the neighbor lady who is 84 years old. I would prefer to be your 90 pound lap dog and still all of your attention. On days when my foster mommy has a hard time I am really good at being her emotional support. Heck, I personally think I would make an amazing support animal for anyone who is looking for that additional love in their life.
____________________________________10/8 UPDATE: Zane continues to lose weight and loves to go for a walk anytime you are up for one. He has started working with a trainer in his foster home to be calmer when passing by other dogs. He needs to be an only dog at this time.___________________________________Zane was the sole companion for a senior citizen who recently had to go to a nursing facility. Zane is a loving boy who can be amazingly agile for an overweight big boxer boy. Zane likes to keep an eye on the neighborhood and will alert you to people going by with a bark. He loves his walks and needs to go on lots of them to lose weight. 2/2/21 9:16 AM

animal.description:
If you are interested in meeting Bruce, you MUST fill out an adoption application on our website: www.BarkAvenuePetHouse.com

Bruce is a big, goofy, lovable guy that is looking for his forever home! Bruce is about 2 years old, neutered, and up to date on vaccinations. Due to his size and features, we think Bruce is mixed with a Great Pyrenees or another type of large breed dog. Bruce is a very sweet and loving dog. However, Bruce is in need of a home where he will have someone who is able to devote a lot of time to training and working with him on trusting the world around him. Bruce has a lot of fear of the unknown and due to his size and strength, he can be a handful at times. He is in need of a family with lots of large dog and guardian dog experience. Due to Bruce's speculated breed mix, it is in his nature to guard his people from strangers (people who live outside the home) or other animals. Bruce likes most dogs, however, due to the amount of training and adjustment time he will need, we feel it is best that he is an only pet at this time. He also is inclined to chase small animals so he can not be in a home with cats or other small pets. It would be best if Bruce DID NOT go to a home with children under 16 years of age due to his size and nature. Despite all of this, Bruce is a dog who truly wants to be a good boy with a family who will help him gain some trust in the world around him.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Terry! I was abandoned by my owners at a Miami animals shelter before being brought to Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I like to play with other dogs, but I can be selective with who I choose to play with. I think I could be a great family pet and would do best in a home with children over the age of 5. I do have a decent prey drive so I should be kept away from cats and other small animals that I might confuse for toys. I would be very content with either an experienced dog owner or a first-time adopter but I would REALLY like to find a home with a big yard for me to run around and play in. I think I'd do best in a busy home, particularly one that has lots of visitors for me to greet! I think I may even be the type of dog that you could take out in public with you as you do your daily activities. I appear to be well-trained, but could always benefit from some further training. I love to go on nice long leashed walks or runs, play with my toys, and snuggle up next to someone I love on the couch!

animal.description:
At this point we don’t know if Tucker will ever walk unassisted or just how far he will progress - but we do know he is at the perfect age to start building that bond with his perfect person(s). We have done everything we can to put him on the best path forward. Regular physio and daily care and assistance in most things are needed to help him grow. He is approximately 28 pounds and growing. With a Catahoula Leopard Dog and Standard Poodle for parents Tucker will likely be a big boy. He has learned to use his speedy wheels and loves to zip about in them, though obviously cannot get in and out of them by himself. He has neither bladder or bowel control but is aware when he needs to “go” and will let you know with a special bark. He has learned a number of commands and is a very, very smart puppy. He loves other dogs, is fabulous with people and children, and like most puppies his age, likes to nibble on fingers if he is overtired or over stimulated. Tucker is an extremely loving and sweet boy who enjoys being a part of the action and would benefit from the company of another dog. His daily needs include Assissi Loop and E-Stim treatments, playtime with toys and his people, a walk, socialization, time in his Help-me-up harness and just some hanging out in his wheels. And though he wears a bellyband, and keeping to an elimination schedule helps, accidents do happen and he may need to be tidied up to keep him clean and dry. While the movement in his back legs has improved since being in our care, and we are hopeful that he will become more independent as he matures, we cannot predict the future for Tucker. Other than we know this sweet pup will make an amazingly loving companion for just the right person or family who have the dedication to helping him grow into his best self. 
Neuter and obedience will be mandatory. Tucker's adoption will include his wheels and a pre-paid physio package with our rehab veterinarian. 

To apply please visit: 
http://www.misfitmanordogrescue.com/adoption-application.php

animal.description:
Ruby is a very sweet Doberman, born September 2015. Ruby has Wobbler Syndrome; however, she has responded very well to medical management. When she came into rescue, she could barelly walk, but she continues to improve. Although she still hasn't mastered going up and down stairs and getting into vehicles, she does well using a ramp. Her very patient foster mom continues to work with her, and she is making progress. Her perfect home will have very few stairs or the possibility of a ramp. It is difficult for Ruby to walk on smooth flooring such as wood and tile so carpet or rugs are needed inside the home. Any resident dogs should be calm and not too pushy. 

Wobbler Syndrome, a disease caused by compression of the spinal cord in the neck area resulting in nervous system problems which make it difficult for the dog to move around normally, 

The suggested adoption donation for Ruby is $300. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Pearl

 

SPECIAL NEEDS

Pearl is a precious 1-year old chihuahua with special needs.  Pearl's back was so badly broken, the veterinarian that first examine Pearl said it was amazing that Pearl even survived such a severe injury...her spinal cord was essentially severed.  After months of physical therapy, Pearl is able to run around with her doggy friends but it is likely that one of her legs will never be completely normal.  She may require a back leg bootie long term for protection but it will not slow her down a bit.  Due to the paralysis, Pearl also requires bladder expression throughout the day but she can poop on her own.

 

DESCRIPTION (BIO)

This adorable young lady loves toys and attention from her people.  She is known to get quite spunky during playtime, yet melts in your arms during a good cuddle session.  Since the veterinarian has requested limited exercise, Pearl enjoys being carried around like the princess she is.  An ideal home for Pearl would be one with lots of patience and understanding.  It is also essential that Pearl continue with her weekly physical therapy until the vet discharges her.  Although she would be fine being the one and only fur-baby, Pearl has spent a lot of time with other dogs and really enjoys playing with them.  Additionally, she recently met our office cat, so it is possible, with proper introductions, Pearl would happily live with cats too. 

 

Won't you consider being a mother of Pearl...or father?

 

Adopters must live in the Los Angeles area.

animal.description:
Wyatt von Elsnig is a beautiful 4 year old German Shepherd. He has a sweet, initially shy personality and gentle demeanor that will draw you in. While he likes to take his time easing into new situations and relationships, once he has the lay of the land, he opens up. Thus far he seems more shy with men, but once he's comfortable, he'll offer you kisses. We think he is likely housebroken. On walks, Wyatt is a bit cautious and can pull if he gets nervous, but with corrections he settles down, even walking nicely next to other dogs when he gets the chance. Off the leash, Wyatt becomes much more social and you’ll see his tail wagging in delight when he gets to go out to the yard around other dogs. He likes to avoid overly-pushy dogs but, other than that, gets along nicely with others. Wyatt knows his new family is out there looking for a dog like him, and he’s ready to come to a feline free home with you.

animal.description: Hi there!  I’m Truffles and I’m a fabulous medium-sized, adult dog, who is looking for a home with an owner or family who wants an affectionate, energetic, and intelligent companion.  I have all sorts of love to give and am just waiting for the right person to come along so that I can shower him/her/them with attention and adoration.  I had a prior experience in a shelter and boy, I sure don’t want to be in one of those again.  But, you ask, “ what would I like”? I would love to get cuddles and take naps together.  Although I’m definitely an in-home kind of gal, some time in the great outdoors would be wonderful. I will thrive with attention and training. I know a couple of commands, but I would be more than happy to learn some other commands as well as some tricks.  I super treat-motivated and my foster mom says that I’m a quick learner.  I’m friendly with other dogs, as long as the other dog accepts me.    I am fully vetted, microchipped, and spayed. animal.description:
Milan is a beautiful old soul looking to make your home complete.

This sweet girl spent her entire pre-rescue life as a backyard dog. She has captured hearts in her foster home and is loving the security she feels as an indoor dog. 

We think Milan is a Shiba Inu/Lab mix. She's intelligent, loving, and active. Once she knows you, Milan is a total love bug who just likes to hang out and be around her people. She is an affectionate girl and likes the be the center of your attention. She will lavish you with attention, too! Give her some belly rubs and see her adorable grin. And she absolutely LOVES her toys! Squeaky toys especially!

Milan is a very vivid dreamer. Her foster mom has seen her talk and "run" in her sleep! We imagine she's dreaming that she is your personal superhero. Not all heroes wear capes--but this loyal girl would probably put one on if that would make you happy!

Although she is a senior, Milan really enjoys to accompany you on a nice long walk. Milan would do best in an adult only home, and she would LOVE to be your only pet. That way she doesn't have to compete for those belly rubs that she loves so much! 

Milan is 55lbs, 8 years young, crate trained, potty trained, a quiet and tidy companion! If you'd like to know more about Milan, please send us an email to adopt@liveloveanimalrescue.org or fill out an application form at liveloveanimalrescue.org.

She does have a medical condition called laryngeal paralysis. This is where there is a narrowing that limits her ability to love air efficently to describe it best. Because of this condition she should limit her activity (which she's not happy about) and avoid getting overly excited. Prlonged periods of either could cause severe respiratory distress to the point of being an emergency. To complicate it further Prudence has separation anxiety most likely because of her pre-SAAP life. This causes her to become very upset when she can't see you. Prudence must crated or contained to a dog proof room when she is unsupervised. To complicate it even further she has a crate anxiety. All of these anxieties cause her to be visibly upset and bark continuously when someone is not within her site. Obviously no one can be at home all the time but it would be best that Prudence find an adopter who is home most of the time or is able to have someone check on her during the day.
All SAAP animals are vet checked, UTD on vaccines, spayed/neutered, micro chipped, and given flea and heartworm preventative as age appropriate.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

We strive to make the best fit for our dogs and to set them up for lifelong success in their new home. Here are requirements for Timmy's new family:
-Must have a 6 foot fence (we do home visits and will be verifying a sturdy, safe fence)
-no apartments
-no children
-must have a compatible dog for Timmy to live with. Resident dog must be spayed/neutered and vaccinated. We do get reference checks.
-adopter must understand that Timmy will take some time to acclimate, gain his trust and feel comfortable in a new environment. Positive, reward-based training only.
Please do not apply to adopt Timmy unless you meet and understand all these requirements. Thank you.

Timmy (or Tim-Tim, as his foster mom calls him) had a rough start to life. He lived with a hunter as an outside dog, and the hunter gave him to someone else where he lived a raised kennel with other hunting dogs. He came into rescue poorly socialized, but has made tremendous strides while at the foster home.

Timmy likes to play with other dogs and finds comfort in their company, so we are seeking an adoptive home with a friendly dog that could show Timmy the ropes and be his BFF. Timmy is fine with cats, and can easily live with a few, if you happen to be a cat lover.

At the beginning of his chapter with our rescue, Timmy was super shy and scared, but now he seeks attention and sleeps in bed with his foster momma. (And a few other beagles).

Timmy likes to go for walks and does fine on leash, as long as you let him use his super beagle sniffer along the way!

Timmy exhibits some signs of separation anxiety, but can be crated (with a little pharmaceutical help) while his foster mom works long hours. We'd prefer that he go to a home where someone is home a fair bit, but he copes with being left when necessary.

We are seeking an adopter who is patient and extremely kind and understanding.

Timmy is a sensitive soul who deserves someone who will go slow and accept him as the sweet, quirky fellow that we have grown to know and love. He's going to take a little extra work, but that's going to make his addition to the right family all the more satisfying.

Timmy is 4 and half years old, neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, parasite-free, and on heartworm prevention. If you're interested in adding this goofball to your family please fill out an adoption application.All animal breeds and ages are a best estimate

animal.description:
Lola is a Belgian Shepherd mix who is 4 years old and we call her our "street dog". Her life before rescue wasn't the greatest, she was dumped when she got pregnant the first time and was finally trapped when she was found pregnant again with 2 of her one year old babies roaming the streets of Oklahoma. Lola is a VERY sweet, gentle girl. She does take a bit to warm up, as you can imagine the human hasn't always been her friend. She does enjoy running and playing with the other dogs in the house, her approach to humans is slow, but once she knows she can trust you, she will come to you for pets and ear scratches. Lola will take a special person that doesn't mind taking a week or two to allow her to adjust to her new home. She is crate and potty trained.

Lola came to rescue with heartworms, she finished her treatment on December 5th. This is all common, especially for a dog that fended for herself for at minimum 1.5 years. She is now healthy and ready to find that forever family to continue to spoil her and show her life doesn't have to be as rough as she started out in life.

Lola's adoption fee is $200.00 which includes DLPP, Bordetella, Rabies, Spay, Microchip and her next dose of heartworm preventative. If you are interested, please complete the

Adoption Application

on our website at

9-21-2020: Gracie is doing well and her kidney values are now in the normal range! Soon we can address her terrible teeth! Keep the good stuff coming her way!

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

UPDATE: The news isn't good but it's not the worst news we have ever gotten. We will do all we can to improve her quality of life and make sure she knows she ma
tters.
From our vet's office:
We got Gracie worked over today and found many things going on. Her bloodwork showed increased white blood cells and an increased kidney value that we are worried about. Doc would like to start her on some IV fluids to help get that down. She has an ulcer on the right eye we want to start vetropolycin to see if we can improve that. Her left does have some minimal vision due to cataracts. Mouth is difficult to examine because she appears painful with it. That's something we will work on more as we go. She has fleas and chronic dermatitis for which we want to start apoquel for. An ear infection in the left ear. We will have mometamax to start for that. 4DX was positive for Lyme so we have doxycycline. Her fecal shows hooks, we have heartgard to get rid of those. We were able to vaccinate today.
So please send some good thoughts and GLOW to little Gracie as we move forward for her. She has suffered

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Meet TLC Rescue's newest intake...little Gracie

Gracie was with some awful people that tried to pull her teeth with pliers and just broke them off.

She appears blind in one eye and has quite a few problems. She is safe right now with one of our vet techs and will be going to our vet on Tuesday.
She will be completely checked out and get blood work and everything she needs. We will see what can be done about her mouth. She is very, very sweet and petite.
I am so glad a kind person intervened and got her and that Chris reached out to me

I won't even say what her old name was. It's Gracie now. All her past is just that...past, never to be seen again. Welcome to your new life, little love

animal.description: Bosti is a graduate of our decompression program for shy and fearful dogs. When he came to us he was very scared to be in the shelter, but who wouldn't be? But, he really blossomed during his time with us. He's curious about other dogs, but has been keeping to himself for the most part. Bosti knows how to walk nicely on a leash and loves tasty treats, like chicken (smart guy). Bosti was brought to PACC as a stray after he climbed a six-foot fence to get to a lady he really wanted to meet, so he'd do best in a home with a secure fenced yard and a patient owner who is willing to give him time and space to become comfortable with his new family. Bosti lived with a family briefly who said he was a little too interested in their cats, so no kitties please! PUPDATE: Bosti spent about a month in a home where we learned that he was housebroken, did great with a 7 year old child, and enjoyed sleeping in bed with his owner. Ask Bosti's volunteer advocate, Robin, about him: rldaniels18@gmail.com BOSTI IS ENROLLED IN THE GOOD DOG PROJECT AT PACC - Read a message from his case manager here: tinyurl.com/gdpmessage - Ask his case manager about him: rachel.jones@pima.gov

animal.description:
DEANA is a sweet, 6-year-old, 50-pound German Shepherd Dog mix.

This beautiful tan and black German Shepherd mix was found living on an abandoned property in rural Georgia where she had her 7 puppies in an abandoned shed.  when people came to do work on the property, they discovered this little family and brought them to animal control.  Deana is now a healthy 50 pounds but when found she was only half that. 

DEANA is a wonderful friend and companion who would be an excellent addition to any family!

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

Finn is a great dog!. He gets along great with children but does not like to share with other dogs. He would be best as an only fur-child and would rather spend his days running and playing. 


WE ARE CURRENTLY OPERATING BY APPOINTMENT ONLY DUE TO COVID-19
Unless otherwise stated, the adoption fees for dogs over 5 months range from $50-$175. Puppies under 5 months are $175.00. Cats over 1 year are $35.00, kittens under 1 year old are $60.00. Dog adoption fees include a microchip. Cats can be microchipped by request for an additional $5.00.
The adoption fee includes the animal's surgery, vaccinations, flea preventative, deworming medication, sample bag of food/treat samples and a free first exam with participating veterinarians. Shelter policy and 2018 Indiana state law decrees all animals must be spayed or neutered prior to leaving the shelter.
WE ARE CURRENTLY OPERATING BY APPOINTMENT ONLY DUE TO COVID-19
Our shelter is open to the public on Monday- Saturday from 8:00 am -5:00 pm EST with the exception of Wednesdays on which we typically open by 1:00 pm. If you would like to make an appointment to meet one of our many adoptable animals, please send an email to us at pvchs@joink.com. animal.description:
NAME: CRICKET
Age: 2 yrs old
Breed: Potcake from Antigua (mix breed hound/terrier)
Sex: male
Weight: 40 lbs 
Location: Coldwater, ON
Spayed/Neutered: YES, I am neutered.
Kids/Cats/Dogs: No young children, they make me nervous. I love to play wih other dogs, but I prefer female dogs. I love to chase cats. Not suited to a home with cats.
Crate/house trained: I am not 100% on crate/house training. I need a lot of time and patience.
Car rides: Nervous at first. Once I get to know you and your car, it is no big deal. I will be good I promise. 
Leash walks: I am good on leash. I have scars on my neck, I am more comfortable and walk much better in a harness. 
Vacc/worming/flea: UTD on vaccinations? Flea/tick, worming? Vet checked? Microchipped?

Hello, my name is CRICKET. I was born on the island of Antigua. Things have happened in my past that only my eyes have seen. I have some scars to prove that some people were not very nice to me. 
I used to live on the streets of Antigua. Once owned, but discarded like trash. I struggled to find food, and survive. Street dogs often perish from hunger, disease, poison, or run over by cars. It's a tough life on the street. A nice lady spotted me, and started to feed me, eventually I was able to get to a vet.
Now I've made the journey to Canada to find my Fur Ever home. I have tested positive for heartworm. What does that mean? Not much really, you would not know I have it. I'm not sick. I have been treated already. I just need to have a blood test in a few months to make sure it's all gone. I'm bouncy and playful, sweet, and sensitive too. I want to please you, and have learned already a few basic commands. I would prefer a quieter home, since I'm not used to busy streets and noises. I love to run and leap through the fields. A large property would be ideal for me. I havent had much experience living inside a house, so I will need someone to help me through patience and structure. I have worn belly bands to prevent indoor marking.  When left alone I get anxious. I may bark, howl, mess, or be destructive inside and/or have anxiety in the crate.
I have proven that with time, exercise and patience I can be crated successfully, and be good in the house with minimal accidents. But this doesnt come easy, it requires a knowledgeable person and the right environment. This could take several weeks, or even months for me to become comfortable. An alternative would be an outdoor heated shed or kennel that I could go in while I cant be watched. I dont mind this option at all, this works for me!
I am a smart guy, I love to cuddle and I love to hang out with my people. My favourite thing is to go out for hikes in the woods. I love to run! I will stay nearby my family. 
I have so much love to give, I will be patient for that perfect home. If you think you have the right environment for me, fill out an application!
Click the application link here:
https://form.jotform.co/83008434566862
fureverfriendsadoption@gmail.com 
Love Cricket ?

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Zeus! Zeus is 4 years young and has had a pretty tough start in life. This sweet fella lived on a 5ft chain with another female companion of his life. A Tail To Be Told Animal Rescue stepped up and took him and his female companion in. Not surprisingly, he also tested positive for heartworms . He received his treatment and now is on monthly prevention. He has made a full recovery and live a long and healthy life thanks to this wonderful rescue. If you like the Boxer personality this is your guy. He is goofy, wiggly and 100% all about getting love and affection. Zeus is doing great with his house training ( bell training) and is already crate trained. He has rocked his board and train program so far and ready for adoption. He knows all his basic commands, working on house manners, door manners, leash walking at a heel and recall. We know Zeus needs to go to a home without kitties or small animals. He would prefer to be the only dog or a submissive female ( He did have a bad experience with another dog attacked him. Since then he has become fearful and can be aggressive when meeting new dogs) We would really like Zeus to find a home before his board and train is completed with Enriched canine training, so he does not have to go back to the rescue.
The trainer will complete a turnover lesson with you as well as give a follow up complementary lesson with you and Zeus to make sure you are set up for success.

Beans had an issue meeting new people when he first came to us - this is now resolved, and he feels confident within a few minutes of meeting someone new.

Beans is one year old and healthy.

animal.description:
This is Banjo...the most handsome, sweet, playful, eager-to-please, goofy, and world's best cuddler!!! He is about a year-old and over 75lbs. He wants to be wherever you are, sitting/lying right next to you or ON you ? He's like that annoying little brother that follows you everywhere, instigates you to play, and wants to do everything you do but that you can't help but love and adore!!! Paloma (Banjo's housemate)  is always quick to correct him and like a good puppy in training, he listens. He is still a big puppy, but he is AMAZING!!! Once he puts his big ol' paw on you and gazes into your eyes, you fall so in-love!!! So if you're looking for a forever love to fulfill your home, family, and heart...Banjo may be your guy! Banjo has been working with a trainer to make him a more polite gentlemen, and it's going very well.  Banjo seems to be generally fearful of new people, and needs to be introduced slowly to new people and situations.. Undersocialized dogs can be easily intimidated or confused by human body language that mimics canine body language - things like maintained eye contact, stiffness, sudden motion, sticking out hands to be sniffed/deliver treats, etc. Banjo's overall excitement combining with this fear in the moment leads to  overreactions. We are looking for an adopter who will be patient and continue with his training.  

-----
To adopt please complete the application at tarnj.org/adopt

If you have any questions at all, please DO NOT use the PetFinder inquiry form. Please email us at info@tarnj.org.

We are all volunteer-run and do our best to respond to every application, if there is a match, within 2-5 days. If you do not hear from us, please check your Junk folder or email us for an update.

animal.description:
This handsome guy is Kashi. He is a three year old, 90 pound Yellow Labrador Retriever and Shepherd mix. He is fully vetted and ready to find his forever family.

Kashi is young boy with lots of puppy energy still! He is big and never taught just how big he is. While he doesn't have a mean bone in his body, his size sometimes gets in the way of his play, like when he knocks you over by accident. He seems to pick up new commands quickly, but he is easily distracted when he sees something like a squirrel or cat (he has a prey drive). In his foster home he is playing with other dogs of different sizes and ages.

Kashi rides very well in the car! He will sit or laydown and stay the whole drive. He will be a great family dog if you give him time to settle down and are willing to work with him on his manners. If you have young children, please consider his size and the fact that he can't stop quickly and plays a little rough, so small children (or adults) could easily be knocked down or pushed over.

If you are interested in adopting Kashi please submit an inquiry directly with Greater Charlotte SPCA by visiting charlottespca.org/adopt.

***Because our rescue is composed entirely of volunteers and we require a home check for each of our adoptable pets prior to them going to their new homes, local applications will take precedence. We will accept out of town applications, but any family further than 60 miles from Charlotte is responsible for finding a representative of a rescue local to them that is willing to perform the home check. All out of town applicants will also have to be willing to drive to Charlotte to meet/pick up the pet as soon as the application is approved.***

animal.description:
Hello, I'm Hazel! Nice to meet you! I am a little nervous at first, but once you get to know me, I'm a total sweetheart! I'm a beautiful and affectionate girl looking for her forever home. If you would like to meet me, schedule an Adoption Appointment at the Allen County SPCA today! I am currently lounging in a fantastic foster home so please allow for a 24 hour notice for a meet and greet appointment. I will need to stay on my special food for allergies but the nice staff will be more than happy to go over all of that with you. Can't wait to meet you!

Weight: 41.40 lbs.

Adoption Price: $100

WANT TO TAKE ME HOME TODAY? SCHEDULE AND ADOPTION APPOINTMENT.
To Schedule An Adoption Appointment:
1. Fill out and submit our online Adoption Application.
2. Please only submit ONE Adoption Application. (Our Application is for general pre-approval, not for a specific adoptable animal).
3. Once received, the Allen County SPCA will review your application. Applications are reviewed in the order they are received.
4. We will contact you to let you know your Adoption Status and schedule an Adoption Appointment. Applications may take up to 1-2 days to process. Please give us a call at the shelter at 260-744-0454 if you have not heard back from us within 48 hours.
5. If you haven't found your perfect match at the shelter, that's okay too - pre-approved applications are valid for 6 months!

Come prepared! Please bring proof of a current rabies vaccine for all pets living in the home. If you have another dog, you are welcome to bring him or her with you so that we can safely perform a dog interaction.

Unfortunately, animals cannot be held for you.

A Special Note from the Allen County SPCA:
Remember, pets are a lifelong commitment. We at the Allen County SPCA ask that you take adding a furry family member to your home seriously, and do your research on the different breeds before adopting. We also ask that you are able to keep up on yearly vaccinations, monthly preventatives, a good diet, daily exercise, training, and most of all, LOVE. If you ever have an issue with a pet that you adopted, please contact us right away; we may be able to help, or we can put you in touch with someone who can. All set? Come in and adopt today!
