American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption.

Sadly, his momma was flooded by Hurricane Sally and lost everything she had and as hard as it was she had to surrender her pups because that is what she felt was the best decision. Jojo is a Chi mix. He was originally picked up as a stray a several years back. He was so scared you couldn’t hardly touch him. This boy has come so far. He’s still timid in new situations and needs some patience to get adjusted and comfortable but he’s the sweetest guy. He’s great with all size dogs and cats. Sometimes they play and chase the cats but never hurt them and will even eat out of the same bowl as them. Jojo May have a lot more gray than the original pic we were sent but this boy still has lots of years and spunk left. He’s a super sweet boy who is doing fantastic in his new foster home. Jojo is around 10 years old and 15ish lbs. He will use a doggy door and loves to go outside. Jojo is utd, hw neg (tested below detectable levels) and neutered. 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Daisy Mae is a sweet, approx. 9 month old black labrador mix.    She is puppy thru and thru!   She loves to run and play outside.  She particularly enjoys chasing tennis balls.   Daisy Mae is playful, sweet and goofy, all at the same time.  She has her favorite rope toy that loves to play with.  She loves kids & other pups alike!  What Daisy Mae really wants is a furever family all of her own!    Won't you please consider this sweet girl?  

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup tested heartworm negative, and is on regular monthly heartworm prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

FYI:   Even though this pup tested heartworm negative, we provide the following procedural information for your information:  Any of our pups who test HW+ are treated with the *slow kill method of treatment.   The *slow-kill method, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.

Dex is a sweet approx. 3 year old Labrador mix.    He is playful, quiet and mild mannered.   He is also clumsy & funny.  If you enjoy tossing a tennis ball to your pup Dex is your boy!  He LUVS tennis balls and fetch.  He especially LUVS fetch when tiny humans throw the ball.   He is very much a lover b ut doesn't care for big scary lawn mowers. Dex is amazing around kids.    Like most rescue pups, this furbaby is HW+, but is currently undergoing the *slow-kill method of treatment (see more information below).  

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heartworm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by her veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet.

*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family.

animal.description:
Greetings!

Todd, is my name and loving is my game!  I was stuck in a shelter for several years. I came in as a stray and I had a girlfriend but she was adopted.  People just kept passing me by.  I was so sad because I didn't understand why. Another dog, Sandy, was getting pulled from my shelter and the nice girl there pleaded for me to be rescued too because I was one of her favorites... so, here I am!

My foster family now knows why I was one of the favorites at the shelter.  I have so much love to give and I adore my foster family so much.  I'm a 7 year old bully mix that is an absolute lovable goof.  My foster family is not sure if I ever lived in a house before and I'm not talking, so this in an ongoing learning experience.

I'm very smart and I have made tons of progress!  I'm perfectly crate trained and definitely treat motivated. I do well on a leash and enjoy my baths. I like hanging out with my new buddies, Sandy and Finn.  A couple of my favorite past times are rolling in the grass and laying on the couch with my foster family. This happy go-lucky boy so wants to hang out with my people.

I'm just a huggable lug that is waiting for just the right arms to hug me just right.

Love, 
Todd


Todd would be best suited in a home with children over 7 years old.  He loves to cuddle with his people, but sometimes doesn't realize he's not a little dog. Technically a senior, adoption fee is $125, but he hasn't slowed down and is active and affectionate. If you would like more information or to set up a meet with Todd, contact his foster dad, Dan, @ 865-919-3437 or thenumber1evild@gail.com.

Unless otherwise noted, all Almost Home dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, and flea & tick preventative.

Please be patient with me, change is hard. I'm under 2 years old and have been in 2 homes, please make the third my last and final home! I promise to do the best I can and be a good pupper for you. animal.description:
Update from foster: Willow has settled in at her foster home and has mastered crate training! She has also been reintroduced to kids and did wonderful with them, although her tail can still be a whip when she is happy (which is most of the time). As she has settled in and gotten used to her surroundings, she barks less, unless of course the door bell rings or someone knocks on the door. She loves her walks but also loves to curl up next toyou and sleep the chilly afternoons away. Willow is still a snuggle-bug, in fact she prefers to snuggle under the covers with you on the cold winter nights. 

Willow, born September 2017, is a Parvo victim. Her fur-sibling died of Parvo, and, when Willow started showing symptoms, she was taken to a shelter to be euthanized. Muddy Paws was contacted, and Willow received treatment and has made a complete recovery. Willow is a little shy at first but once she warms up to you, she loves to snuggle and has unlimited kisses. She is energetic and loves to go for walks and run around the fenced yard. Willow gets along with other dogs and is indifferent to cats. She is potty-trained and working on crate training. She has some separation anxiety so she prefers to have people around as much as possible as she doesnt like the crate yet and can be a little destructive and quite noisy when she is alone. Willow likes to let you know when she hears any weird noise (like the toilet flushing, etc) so apartment life would not be a good fit for her. She has been known to nip and her tail can be classified as a secret weapon so she would prefer to be around children 10 years old or older.

The suggested adoption donation for Willow is $350. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Did I catch your eye? Learn more about me by reading my profile below; I just might be your new best friend! Apply on our website
(

https://www.healingheartsrescue.org/adopt

)

to

set up a private meeting or check below for my adoption event schedule.

Age: 2 years

Weight: 65 pounds

Dog friendly: Not currently, maybe with some proper training

Cat friendly: Unknown

Kid friendly: Best with no kids or dog savvy older kids

Potty trained: Yes

Crate trained: yes, not not a fan of it when people aren't home

Hello, My name is Kaia and I love squirrels, chipmunks and being outside. My early days involved some difficult situations. I had two mean sisters. Since being rescued I am working on doing my best interacting with a loving family. I love being outside and playing so much, I forget that I weigh 65 pounds and get a little goofy. I do best with a fenced yard and plenty of room to run. I have been through basic manner training and am excellent in my potty habits. I am a super fast learner and I am very smart.

Let's talk about Walks!!! I love, love, love, love them. I have a lot of energy and love to walk and run with my owners. I have been working hard on loose leash walking but sometimes my nose overtakes my brain and I forget to walk when I smell squirrelies or see other doggies. After a day of good exercise, I like to crash peacefully around where the family is or put myself in my kennel. Regarding my kennel, I don't mind sleeping there but want to be with my family as much as possible. I have some separation anxiety and don't always like the kennel, when they are gone.

If you know pitties, you know we're really comedic, loving and loyal. I'm all those things, and love to snuggle on the couch and on the bed. Also as a typical pittie, I can be a bit bullheaded. I thrive in a home with a strong pack leader who gives me the correct direction I need to thrive. I would do best in a home with either no kids or older, dog savvy kids as I tend to try to take advantage of their weakness if given the chance. I love meeting all people, including kids, outside of my home tho and can be a perfect angel when you tell me I need to be.

I can't wait to find my forever family. Do you think it might be you?

Adoption Fee: $195

INTERESTED IN MEETING ME?

If you'd like to arrange a private meeting or begin the adoption process, please fill out an adoption application by visiting

https://www.healingheartsrescue.org/adopt

**Note on breed and age determination:

Breed and age are often determined on appearance, our own knowledge, veterinarian advice, and/or information from the sending shelters or previous owners. Most of our adoptable dogs were previously stray dogs with little history, we can't be 100% sure of a dog's breed mix, and unless there is a specific date of birth listed, we can't be 100% sure of a dog's age. Additionally, our assessments of a dog's interactions with other dogs, cats, or children are based on OUR experiences. Your experience may differ.

ADOPTION FEE INCLUDES:

Wellness check

Spay/neuter (puppies adopted with required spay/neuter certificate)

Age appropriate vaccines - rabies as required by law and distemper combo or proof of positive titer test

Heartworm test if over 7 months of age

Fecal test and/or deworming for parasites

Microchip



~ Healing Hearts rescue will also provide dental procedures, bloodwork, surgeries, and/or any other additional vet work as needed while dogs are in our care.

~ Adoption fees are non-negotiable and fees are listed on the dog's profile

~ Adoption fees can be paid the following ways with the required sales tax (7.525%) added:

PayPal

Credit Card

Cash

WANT TO HELP SAVE MORE DOGS?

Healing Hearts Rescue is a nonprofit, foster-based rescue

located in the Twin Cities area of Minnesota

that is 100% funded through adoption fees and donations

. We are excited for you to join us on this mission to save the lives of dogs in need.

We believe every dog deserves to be loved as true members of a family and are committed to fulfilling that dream one dog at a time! Sign up to foster, volunteer or donate on our
website

Healing Hearts rescue will also provide dental procedures, bloodwork, surgeries, and/or any other additional vet work as needed while dogs are in our care.

animal.description:
Meet Cooper!
Cooper is a Belgian Malinois mix born November 2019 who is super smart, tons of fun high energy, and a total love bug. 
He was rescued in July and was only 45 pounds, but has been putting on weight ever since . 
Sometimes he can get a little too excited and overwhelm new friends, but generally he’s great with other dogs and loves to run and wrestle with his foster brother. When he’s by himself,  he loves to play and chase sticks and toys. 
Cooper definitely needs a backyard with a tall fence because he can jump really high. Cooper hasn’t met too many cats yet, but seems to mostly ignore the neighbor’s cat when he sees them on walks.
Cooper has been working on jumping. Most of the time, he’s just excited to give you a huge, but he’s still making progress on being calmer inside the house. He’s definitely not a destructive dog, but does need attention and supervision in the house because he’s so curious and energetic. Cooper can get nervous when he sees a flat hand or rolled up newspaper, but he’s made a lot of progress with this since being at his foster home.

Cooper is heartworm negative, neutered, and up to date on shots and vaccines. 
He hasn’t had an accident in the house since being neutered. He’s does great in a crate as well. 
Cooper loves playing, chewing toys, and even bath time. He would make a great family dog, but would be best without small children.

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
There is nothing better than a big ole Hound Dog and Trapper is the perfect one if you love the breed! He is a Black and Tan Coonhound around 12-18 months old. This boy is fun loving and playful. Like most hounds, he probably got a sniff of some wonderful smell and took off to follow his nose. Before he knew it, he was far from his home and lost. We tried for several weeks to find his owner but no one has claimed him. Trapper is now ready to find a new home and a fresh start. Hounds require a fenced yard to keep them safe from doing what nature has taught them to do and that is follow their nose. This sweet boy has shown us that he is such a great dog. He is doing so well on his house training and loves the company of other dogs and all humans, big and small. Cats would not be recommended due to his breed and we insist on a secured and big fenced yard. Trapper came to us under weight and currently weights about 60 lbs. He is enjoying every meal and will soon blossom. Trapper is neutered and fully vetted and ready to share the couch with his new family. If you are interested please email at ccrtennessee@gmail.com
ADOPTION FEE REQUIRED. Contact ccrtennessee@gmail.com.

Schotzie

Welcome Schotzie to Gray Mutts!

We rarely take large dogs anymore, but when one of our fabulous volunteers reached out for help for this girl, we couldn't say no.

Schotzie had a loving owner that passed away, then sadly was not given the care she needed. She was living outside, covered in fleas and dirt.

She's 9 years old, and in dire need of a dental and a hw test and updates to all vaccines.

Please consider making a donation to this senior purebred Dobie! She's a fantastic dog, and once she receives the care she needs, I have no doubt she'll be a stunner!

*Update!

Schotzie is doing great!! She's gaining weight and her coat is improving but we did find that she is heartworm positive and we've started the treatment process. The entire cost for the heartworm treatment is $609. Any donation towards her care will be greatly appreciated, it all adds up! Let's help this beautiful senior get healthy

No Cats!

animal.description:
Archer came to our rescue after being picked up as a stray. He doesn't know his front ankles aren't 'normal' as he gets around just fine. This condition is Angular Limb Disorder and attempting surgeries to resolve could make his situation worse. While he wouldn't be a great running companion he still loves going for walks and short jogs. Long or strenuous walks could make him sore, so his family would want to avoid that as he would go if asked.

This handsome boy is a happy, outgoing, gentle soul. He loves humans of all sizes and ages. Being with his humans and getting attention is his very favorite thing. He lives with lots of other dogs and is fine with everyone unless they are nasty to him; he won't be bullied by anyone. He is good around the cats in his foster home who are very dog savvy. 

Archer has excellent house manners and is crate trained. He is engaged with his humans and treat motivated so would do well with training. He already has great recall and will sit for treats. He loves going for rides and would be a great go-everywhere dog. 

Archer is fully vetted - current vaccines, neutered, microchipped, and on flea/tick and heartworm prevention.

animal.description:
Chia

Will you love and protect me?

I would love to quarantine with you! I came from a sad situation where I was one of many dogs and as a result I was left alone a lot and didn't get the nurturing and socialization I needed.

That is in the past though and I am young (almost 2 years old) with my whole life ahead of me. I am in a foster home now and I learn a lot from watching my foster brother.

My foster mom has shown me what it is like to be loved and petted and I LOVE it and can't get enough! If you are patient with me it will be worth the wait and I will give you unconditional love. I am very loyal once I trust you and my foster mom even calls me a shadow. I want nothing more than a forever home where I can be petted, love, and grow.

I would do well in a home with 1 (maybe 2) dog that is easy going so I can learn. I could be an only dog but it may take me longer to learn without pack mates to show me the ropes. A home with young, active children is probably not for me but I do well with older children.

My foster mom would be happy to answer questions, show you more pics, or even a video that shows my silly side!

Chihuahua/Pug mix

Almost 2 years old

Fully Vetted and Spayed

$125 Adoption Fee

animal.description:
Sage is a wonderful dog who has probably one of the softest short coats you will ever feel.  Everyone who gets the opportunity to pet her comments on how soft she feels.  Once you are close to her you'll also learn why we call her Snortle Pig as she makes this grunting/snorting type sound when being loved.  She has the sweetest brown eyes with which she shows so much emotion.  You'll also know when she's happy or excited because she'll sing you a song and her whole body wiggles.  You best watch out for her tail which can get you and feel like getting hit with a whip.  If she's under the dining room table it'll sound like a game of pinball going on with how fast and furious it can be.  She's not big on kisses but she shows plenty of affection and sometimes tries getting in your lap despite being 60ish pounds.  

She is crate trained, house-trained, leash trained, and is very well listened.  Sage is also bike trained and treadmill trained and has no problem with either and she's never met exercise of any kind that she doesn't like.  She loves to play tug or Jolly Ball with you but isn't a throw a stick and fetch type dog.  She seems to fall in love with her Jolly Ball and then chews it to pieces over time and you have to sneakily throw it out eventually and surprise her with a new one.  If she sees you do this she'll most likely just stare at your trash can and not play with the new ball.  She does require quite a lot of exercise and would not do well in a slow paced environment.  Sage isn't the best with not getting on furniture, as she loves getting on beds and even more so if you let her under the covers. She loves a good morning snuggle in the bed and will let you know if she requires some petting by boxing you with her sandpaper paws as she looks at you lovingly.  That soft coat of hers is probably not the best feature for winter here and she loves being under blankets or in her jacket.  You'll know if she's cold as she will visibly get the shivers.  She'll also lay or stand as close to the woodstove as possible.

Sage is very food driven and will certainly let you know when she's hungry, which, come to think of it, is all the time.  Her eyes go back and forth from you to the pantry where the dog food is stored politely asking with her eyes "Is it time? - the foods in here - do you know the foods in here? - is it time yet?"  This action will be repeated regularly somewhere around 7:30am and 5pm daily.  She will also try to steal food and you have to be careful as she'll contort herself in whatever way required to snatch that dozen cookies off the counter you were planning on sharing with friends or family.  

We believe Sage will make for a great companion.  She is very unsure of herself and nervous around other dogs and we and a trainer have worked a lot with her to help her with this.  She still has plenty of work left though. Although she does well at being in a controlled environment with other dogs, we feel she would do best in a home as the only dog and would not be  the type of dog that enjoys dog social activities. Although she lives with kids, due to her insecure nature, we feel she would do best in an adult-only home. She also has a strong prey drive prey drive and should not live with cats or other small animals.   

Sage is looking for a patient and experienced owner who can help her with her insecurities. She will love you unconditionally as she loves our family.  She would love a home with lots of space and land or a big fenced yard.  She's not the type of dog who has ever tried to escape or get away from us, probably because she'd then be unsure where her next meal might come from.  Sage really is a wonderful dog, she's going to make someone very happy and feel very loved, and it's sad that we cannot be the fit for her and we're looking to provide her with the best opportunity for the life she deserves.
animal.name: Sage

animal.description:
Goodwin is such a sweet, handsome boy, his foster mom says that she has watched him transform in so many ways. His ears and forehead wrinkles will melt your heart! He loves being around his people and will take every opportunity available to cuddle. His foster mom calls him her shadow ?? Though he is estimated to be around 5 years old, he has a lot of energy and loves zooming around the yard and going on walks. He walks well with his harness but does pull at times. 

Goodwin does great with other dogs but he’s not into having any cat friends. He’s been in a house with children and has done excellent. He is very vocal, his foster mom is working on that, and although he’s improved we think a house with older children would be best. He lives with a 6 year old and Goodwin has been amazing. .

He does great in his crate. He can sit, lay and give paw. Goodwin loves getting his neck and chest rubbed. He has so much love to give and he’s learned and grown so much in just the couple months he’s been with us.

You must be over 21 and a home owner to adopt me. Please visit www.pittiesandpurrs.org to fill out an application. For further information contact adoptpitties@gmail.com

animal.description:
Hi there!

My name is Blossom! I LOVE humoons and to snuggle up with them! Those 4 legged things called cat though, yummy yummy I love them a little too much and can not be in a home with them. I am a huge fan of walks and love to visit with those small humoons. Please let me into your home, Id love to keep your feets warm!!

I am currently in a foster home and not at HSNBA, if you are interested in meeting me, please contact the nice folks at HSNBA so they can put you in contact with my foster family to set up a meet & greet. E-mail HSNBA at adoption@hsnba.org, call us at: (830) 629-5287 or stop by and speak with the folks at HSNBA at 3353 Morningside Dr. to get your information sent over to my foster home. My foster family is the best and can give you more information on me.

I have tested heartworm positive. This means I have a parasite and need treatment. While my friends at HSNBA desperately want to help me, the shelter is too stressful an environment to undertake treatment, and the treatment itself is very expensive. The shelter has a few options to help with treatment, and if I steal your heart you should talk with them and your vet about what my treatment is like. For more information on heartworms, please visit the American Heartworm Society here https://www.heartwormsociety.org/pet-owner-resources/heartworm-basicsHSNBA lists all animals online from the moment of intake, and our listings are updated automatically every midnight. Some of these animals may not be available for adoption at this moment, but you can always call the shelter at 830-629-5287 for clarification on the adoption process or the animal's current status.

animal.description: Meet Carter, a housebroken, four-year-old pit-bull, terrier mix. Carter loves going on walks, sniffing all the smells, and meeting new people. He is looking for a human who will take him on his next big outdoor adventure! He is polite and eager to meet folks who pet him, but he is not very interested in meeting other canines. Carter is not a big fan of a crate, but that is okay because be doesn't need one! He is house trained, and will politely scratch at the door to let you know it's time to stretch his legs, or have a potty break. Carter is very mellow, and is fine being left on his own indoors while you are out running errands. He also likes to be around his people and enjoys getting moral support. Carter has been through a lot in his short life, but he has not let it get him down! He is more mellow than most pups his age, which is great for a home that is looking for a chill pup to pamper. He is a cuddly, friendly, loving, calm, and gentle soul who is looking for the next lucky person to share his life. He is loyal to his humans, and will look at you with his big striking eyes when he wants attention. Carter would thrive in a home with adults only where he can be the solo top dog. He would love a home where he can sniff the backyard to his heart's content, but would do well in an apartment with outdoor access for potty breaks. Carter likes creature comforts, and relaxing with his humans and cuddling. He is just happy to have a human to love. Come meet Carter, he wants to cuddle!

animal.description:
Meet Rocket, an 11month old male Belgian Malinois who lives up to his name! He is a high energy and drive Malinois through and through, and is looking for a loving and experienced forever home. In the right home he will thrive and be a wonderful companion. 

Rocket is very energetic, strong and lacking training. He has a lot of energy that he needs help channeling in the right ways, as typical working breeds do. He will require a GSD or Malinois experiences home, that knows how to train and work with the breed. 

Rocket is still working on his social skills with other dogs. At this time he should be an only dog in the home. With proper training and structure he could get better with other dogs. We do not recommend him with cats. 

Since he can be jumpy and mouthy, he needs a home with kids over 15, adult only preferred. 

Rocket is in the process of being neutered and will be neutered prior to adoption. He is UTD on shots and microchipped. His adoption fee is $500.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.BONDED WITH BARBIEFate brought Muffy and Barbie together in the same foster home and now they are besties! Their destiny is leaving for their forever home as a bonded pair. These two start playing the minute their eyes open in the morning and they will continue until bedtime if allowed. These two love to do almost everything together including galloping in and out side-by-side for potty breaks, patrolling the property, and digging holes in the yard. Muffy is a sweet and sassy 5 year old Pyr mix who likes to supervise humans cooking in the kitchen and tends to want to help. She is a good-natured and well-mannered girl who loves to go on walks and rides and is always ready for her next adventure but is not at all opposed to an afternoon nap or cuddles with her foster mom on the couch. She will alert her humans to any potential activity occurring outside and when she's not guarding she likes to relax in the yard or tend to a good hole she and Barbie have started. Muffy knows several commands, including "sit," "shake," and "come" but typical of Pyrs, may decide not to do these unless you make it worth her while. Muffy need a home without cats or other small pets. Muffy does NOT like sharing food or treats with Barbie so they need to be separated while eating. Muffy and Barbie are being fostered in Tacoma, WA.

All our dogs require secure VISIBLE fencing. All current pets in adoptive home must be spayed/neutered and up to date on vaccinations.

Adoption Fee: $350

All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations.

Transport Fee: $300

Transport fee includes the cost of transport plus the Health Certificate required for USDA approved transport.

Adoption applications can be found on our website: www.greatpyrsandpaws.org

https://greatpyrsandpaws.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=5959

Northwest adopter pays cost of transport to independent transport company. Transport is arranged by GPPR.

Adoption Process: This is not a first come, first serve organization. We will process applications within 48 business hours of receiving them. The application must be completed in full including first and last name, complete address including city and state, complete veterinarian information(this will be checked and all pets must be neutered or spayed, up to date on all vaccines, and dogs must be current on heartworm prevention) and the name of all current pets in the household. We are 100% volunteers and I will not subject anyone who is giving of themselves and their time to hostile conversations. Please be patient with us. We are not paid for our endless hours and are looking for the BEST home for the babies in our care.
We will process your information and an email will be sent to the email you provide on the application within 48 hours.

animal.description:
Mishka here! I am looking for some new digs away from my son! He has been following me around for the past year and not giving me any personal space! Kids! I was in a pretty bad place not long ago, being abandoned by my owner but a wonderful lady came along and got me away from that situation. She took me to a beautiful place in Montana where I now have room to run and play and get away from my son! I am learning how to walk on a leash and do other basic commands and will soon be ready to have my own family. I am not too sure about other dogs but I suppose a mellow male would be OK. I do like kids but the small ones seem to fall over a lot when they are around me and I don’t want to hurt them so the bigger kids would probably be best.

From Moonsong: Mishka is about 5 years old, spayed and up to date on her shots. She is in a 3 week training program in Montana and when finished, will be a great dog for almost anyone. She is guarded around other dogs so might do best in a home with no other dogs or a mellow male. She has been around young kids but we do feel because of her size, older kids would be best as she does get excited and could possibly knock a smaller child down. She is a sweet, very energetic dog who would love to be someone’s running partner or be trained for skijoring. She will need some patience as she has little experience being inside and will need some house training. She is also a digger so a secure fence with a dig guard at the bottom is essential. If you’re looking for that special dog that is longing for the love and attention she deserves, take another look at Mishka. She wants to go home with you!

animal.description:
Clara is a very sweet pocket pittie mix, born March 2019 and weighing in at only 43 lbs.. When rescued, Clara and her 7 puppies were strays in Missouri. She is a sweet girl who just wants to be loved on. She loves everyone and is great with other dogs. This smart girl is also completely house trained and knows sit, shake, and down. Clara's puppies found their forever home and now she's looking for hers!

Before applying to adopt Clara, you need to be familiar with your local breed-specific legislation regarding Pit Bulls. Applicants must live within 50 miles of the Omaha/Council Bluffs area.

The suggested adoption donation for Clara is $350. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
PAWS is currently closed due to COVID-19.  The animals are receiving the same high level of care as always.  During this time, we are taking application over the phone.  Until we can safely to resume normal operations, we will be taking deposits and doing adoptions by appointment only on Wednesday evenings, 5 - 7 PM and Saturdays from noon until 3.  We know it’s difficult to choose a lifetime companion animal from a picture but it’s been working out well for our adopters and most importantly, for the animals in our care. The financial impact is obvious but we're committed to keeping our community and volunteers as safe as possible and providing the best of care for our animals.  Any donations are greatly appreciated to help PAWS provided that care.  Thank you.

As you may know, PAWS was one of the rescue groups called upon by the Illinois Department of Agriculture over the Labor Day weekend to help with the surrender of over 300 dogs and cats.  These are some of those dogs.  The breeds include German Shepherd Dogs, Australian Shepherds, Great Pyrenees, Bernese Mountain Dogs and a few Newfoundlands.  We’ve spent this past week bathing, trimming, vaccinating and vetting these animals thanks to the heroic efforts of the staff at our vets office and the dedication of our PAWS volunteers.  The dogs were in deplorable condition, matted and covered with clumps of mud and sadly, their own waste.  They are no longer living that life.  We will be offering these deserving animals for adoption and are doing everything possible to have them into approved adoption homes as quickly as possible.   Please be patient.  Our volunteers are returning calls and processing applications as fast as they can.  If you are interested in one of these animals, please call our office at 217-243-7297 and leave a message expressing your interest.  Repeated calls will only slow down the process.  Thank you for your patience and understanding.  Now, on to the dogs.

This guy is Bolt and he’s a favorite with the volunteers at PAWS.  With his great personality and his gentle demeanor, he’s earned the spot as a favorite.  Bolt for some reason is not a fan of small dogs, cats and kiddos, especially younger ones so please, no little animals or kids younger than teens.  Bolt’s coat will be gleaming white again in short order with good nutrition and proper, consistent grooming.  Bolt weights right at 80 pound.  He’s thin so a few extra pounds will be good.  His adoption fee is $200

All of our animals are provided with age appropriate vaccinations, spayed/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption. 
PAWS has added the H3N2/H3N8 combo flu vaccine to its shot protocol. Every dog is being vaccinated upon intake, however we urge adopters to get a second flu shot for their new family member to ensure as much protection against the flu as possible.
To meet our incredible dogs and offer them the love they deserve, stop by PAWS on Friday, Saturday or Sunday from 10 - 4 PM, call us at 217-243-7297. We do applications in person or over the phone. You can also see pictures on our Facebook page, PAWS Jackson.  With an approved application, a deposit will hold your new best friend for up to 1 week to allow you time to come to PAWS.  This deposit is not refundable nor transferable.

animal.description:
****** PLEASE READ THIS IN ITS ENTIRETY ... APPLICATIONS FOR ELLIE ARE CURRENTLY PAUSED *****

When Ellie is ready for a new home, she MUST have the companionship of another dog. The resident dog must be gentle and obedient so Ellie can learn the ropes in the proper manner. Ellie seeks the company of other dogs and finds comfort in being with them. Therefore, the first requirement for potential adopters is that there must be a dog already living in the home. The second requirement is that she needs a human who is SUPER patient. She needs constant coaxing and reassurance, but once she has bonded with her human, she will stay close by. She still is "high strung", meaning that if someone drops anything on the floor or a door slams or someone yells, Ellie is *instantly* running for cover. Ellie isn't your typical come-when-you're-called kind of dog, lying next to you on the sofa while you watch TV. She will come say hello, allow herself to be petted, then she will retreat to her doggy friend(s). 
**************************************************
She still has a long way to go so she won't be available for adoption for a while yet. 
Please keep watching our FB and IG accounts for updates! We'll gladly post when she's ready for the next phase of her life and when we'll be accepting applications for her again!! ...Thanks!!! 

******************************************************************************************************************************************

Our little friend Elle is still very withdrawn and scared. In the best interest of this pup, we have sent her home with our Animal Control Supervisor for some TLC.
**
Officer Michele has 2 dogs at home that will support Miss Elle and help her come out of her shell.
**
After Elle has had time to acclimate to her new surroundings, Officer Michele will be able to see what her personality is like and assess what her needs are.
**
We will post a follow up when we think she is ready to go to a foster home LOCAL TO OR IN Montclair, as she will still need to be treated by our veterinarian for heartworm.
**
Thank you to all who expressed interest in Elle and watch our Facebook and Instagram pages for updates!!! 
************************************************************************************************************************************
Elle is an adorable blue heeler mix who is terrified of absolutely everything.... Noises scare her, people scare her, outside scares her. We have been trying to work with her quietly and slowly since her arrival here. She had tested positive for heartworm and we are awaiting treatment protocol from our veterinarian, but since everything has been shut down, we are in standby mode. Eventually, her heartworm will be assessed by our veterinarian and a protocol will be developed to treat her heartworm, which will involve monthly trips to/from our veterinarian here in town. Therefore, applicants must live in the close vicinity to accommodate her heartworm treatment schedule. 

Elle would probably do best in a QUIET home without children, with someone who will help coax her out of her shell BUT not push her too far, too fast. We think she might be a flight risk, she would need to be crated at night and supervised WELL during the day. We suggest keeping the leash on her and keeping her tethered to your waist so wherever you go, Elle goes. This helps her bond with her person and keeps her out of trouble. 

Elle is responsive with other dogs and might do well in a home where there is a calm dog she can rely on, and follow to help her build her confidence. BUT please keep in mind that she has been so shut down that we haven't been unable to test her with other animals, it wouldn't have been fair to try to assess her in her current mental state. 

Since Elle is such a special case, we must take every precaution possible to place her in the proper home. This means that sorting through the applications takes a little longer because we are more restricted than as if placing a well-adjusted dog. 
So if you have already submitted an application for Elle but do not meet the criteria above, your application will not be processed. We are only contacting applicants who might fit Elle's specific needs, we hope everyone can understand. 

That being said, if you are interested in Elle and understand the responsibilities of caring for a special needs dog like her, then please submit an application and we will contact you as soon as we can. (MS 3-26-20)

animal.description:
Contact THIRD COAST ANIMAL RESCUE at: thirdcoastanimalrescue@gmail.com or https://www.facebook.com/thirdcoastanimalrescue/ with adoption inquiries

Your first impression of Joy is going to be that she's skittish, fearful, and high maintenance socially. You'll probably wonder why her name is Joy. What you aren't seeing in that first meet is her amazing ability to trust and her sheer joy in some of the simple things.

She loves to run, she will alternate between leaping around like a gazelle and running with her butt tucked under for maximum speed! Joy loves other dogs and cats (much to their dismay). She will get along even with old grumpy dogs but takes a bit to learn their signals for 'no'. Ideally, Joy should have an equally energetic dog to play with. The good thing is that she mostly understands that inside is cuddle, nap, or quiet play time and outside is run around like a crazy dog time as long as the other dogs are being calm, too. She has done quite well with indoor cats but the outdoor cat in her foster home was a bit too indulging of some of her bad antics and now she tries to play with him by mouthing on him, which he doesn't like.

Joy is mostly crate trained and partially housebroken. If she gets to go potty on a schedule like a puppy would then she doesn't have any accidents. She is calm and quiet in her crate but will have occasional accidents if she has to wait too long or if she drank too much.

She can be skittish, she will not do well with anyone that uses negative reinforcement/punitive measures. She has responded well to positive reinforcement and blossoms quickly in new environments with those methods. She should not go to a home with small children, but should do well with teenagers. Once she gets the flow of her new home and some treats she will even do well with a few visitors over.

Joy LOVES soft toys and will hoard them. She will either drag them all into her crate or pick a corner of the house near the person she trusts most to hoard them and fall asleep. In fact, when she first gets to a new home or when she doesn't have access to toys she tends to do a lot of pacing. Toys help make her feel secure and she doesn't destroy them.

PLEASE HELP US NETWORK THIS BEAUTIFUL spayed female, Akita, 6 years old a new Kimiko is in foster waiting to be adopted. The foster family are really working with her and doing great. She loves belly rubs and butt scratches! She also does really well in the bath and likes water! She is very bouncing likes to dance and run around our big yard! She is very sweet. She needs some work on her excitement because she does jump. She is working on commands of place, lay down and crate! She can shake, sit pretty, stay and sit. She gets along very well with our other Akita Rosie! She still would prefer to sort of stay separate if the pack outside but loves to cuddle with them inside. You do have to watch the other dogs and her because her personal space bubble is pretty big and she doesn't like if you are paying attention to her and another dog comes close. She has growled a few times due to personal space. She has done well on walks but needs to work on walking next to you because she does pull quite hard. She also does well in the car but needs reminders to say in the backseat. Food and toys have been great she will even drink out of the same bowl of water as the other dogs while they are drinking. She will take treats nicely with the other dogs present. Toys she doesn't play much but doesn't mind if the other dogs are playing with the toys. She does get excited when she doesn't come out of her crate and will grab anything blanket shoe, etc. and try and run around with it! She does get board in the kennel and will chew on whatever is inside bed or blanket but has done better with chew toys inside her crate. We did have one major scuffle between her and our male dog over play time. They both play loud and hard sometimes need reminders on when to stop. I always make sure they are supervised. She does have some dominate behaves such as marking and kicking up grass. We have been working on training out of her and is going really well. She is Overall very happy girl! An adoption application can be downloaded from the DHS website www.dekalbhumanesociety.org. 


*BEFORE ADOPTING ANY DOG, PLEASE RESEARCH THE BREED TO MAKE SURE THEY'RE A PERFECT MATCH FOR YOUR FAMILY LIFESTYLE*

animal.description:
Breed: Chihuahua X
DOB: 12/2018
Gender: male
Altered: yes
Coat: medium
Size: small
Color(s): tan with white
Description:

Hi, I'm Scruffy, a Chihuahua X who was one of 16 dogs rescued from a single family home. We all were not socialized and I was in the worse shape with a broken jaw. It's been repaired and I'm waiting for my special someone to make me a part of their family.

I've been in two foster homes since I've been with C.A.R.L. In my first foster home I lived with other dogs and made tremendous progress and I was doing really well. I'd run around the house and I'd try to get the other dogs to play with me. I'll need a playful and easy-going brother and/or sister in the home who will not only play with me but show me the ropes too. I learned to walk around my foster parents comfortably, but I still wasn't comfortable taking food from them. I was pet every day and eventually they were able to pick me up, but I wasn't entirely comfortable when they did. They sadly moved out-of-state, but I was lucky enough to go into a new foster home.

My second foster mom calls me Sunny. Scared and unsure of my new foster mom and new foster home, I would cower in a corner or hide in my crate. My crate is left available to me so I always have a safe place to be, but I decided rather quickly that I prefer being outside of the crate and now I don't want to go in it. I'm fed in the crate so I feel comfortable should I need to be put in it to go to a vet appointment.

My second foster mom has been allowing me to approach her at my own pace. She can only get close to me on my own terms. I appreciate that she is allowing me to do this as I slowly learn to trust. I do come when called, but still keep my distance. I'll need a patient and loving person who will continue to work with me to help build my confidence and trust. My foster mom says she can see I want to join them on walks, but she hasn't attempted to yet as in my first foster home I wasn't a fan at being leashed up. I'd do the alligator roll. She'll try a harness once I get more comfortable and she can pick me up. I'm sort of house trained as I will go outside via a doggie door, but if it's raining or I have no way to go out I'll do my business inside without warning. My foster mom is using training pads when I can't get outside.

If you have the love and patience that I need as I continue to learn to trust, fill out an application to meet me.

Additional information: *Current on shots

If you haven't already you may read their story below.

16 DOGS RESCUED FROM SINGLE FAMILY HOME....

Even when times are financially tough for our rescue, we try our hardest to help out when we are needed. A family, who was in over their heads because their dogs were not spayed or neutered, reached out to the rescue community for help. They initially said that there were around 9 Chihuahua mix dogs.

On Sunday, four C.A.R.L volunteers drove two vans loaded with crates to South Central Los Angeles to assess the situation. It was far worse than expected. All of the dogs had lived their entire lives outside on a cement patio with very little human touch. They were curious and wanted the treats we brought, but were very scared at the same time and would not let us pick them up.

It took almost 3 hours to catch 4 female Chihuahua mixes, 4 males and 7 puppies. The mother dogs had dug a deep hole under the cement patio about 6 inches in diameter. The puppies (who we think are about 4 to 5 weeks old) were packed inside and not easily accessible.

In the very corner of the yard was a large, old dog chained to the wall. He had broken free from his collar so the family used phone cords to secure the heavy, metal chain around his neck. The dog, who we named "Sam", had severe fly strike on his ears, scabs on his hind legs and sides from sleeping on concrete and was extremely malnourished. The family said they kept him chained up as a guard dog and also to keep him from hurting the little dogs. We approached him with caution, but he was eager to get to know us and came out of hiding for treats and love. He pushed his big head into our hands and we all instantly fell in love with him. We knew that we needed to save him too.

After a lot of convincing, the family finally agreed to let us take Sam. In all, we brought back 16 dogs (this includes the 7 puppies). One of the other females looks to be pregnant too and we will verify this with an ultrasound this upcoming week. .

After returning to our sanctuary, all of the dogs were situated with comfy beds, food and fresh water. In a few days after they have had time to decompress, they will all go to the vet for care.

The two moms with puppies are in a temporary foster home. They were covered from head to toe in fleas and ticks. Each puppy had at least 8 ticks on them. Several have skin infections that need immediate treatment.

animal.description: Meet Percy! I am a two year old Pit Bull mix who has been waiting for a Harrisburg home since September. But I've been in shelters even longer than that, because I was pulled from another shelter since I didn’t get much attention from adopters. I really need a home -- it's been hard to live in small kennels this long. I have a lot of energy and really like to run around; however, I'm a gentleman on the leash. I'll walk right by your side. I will need plenty of exercise for sure and a family committed to providing me with continued training. I would do best with kids over 12 years old as I do tend to guard my resources (bones, food, etc.). I also get mouthy when excited and at times forget my good boy skills! I do know a lot of commands and am pretty smart, so I am sure learning new things will be a breeze. I played off leash with a dog here and did okay! Like many bully breeds, I have a rougher play style, so a dog that can keep up with that is necessary. No little dogs for me! A dog my size or larger is best. I will also need a feline-free home as well. If you’d like to get to know me more, ask my friends about me, Percy!

animal.description:
Meet Handsome Tommy. This shy fellow was found scared and confused after his owner dumped him. We quickly realized this incredibly shy boy was one of the sweetest dogs in our rescue. Extremely guarded an unsure the first introduction, but affectionate and loving the next time. 

Handsome Tommy has spent time with our trainer to make sure he can get along with other dogs. Tommy quickly joined his pack. He went on walks daily and spent quality time with other dogs. 

Tommy loves the ladies and a bit guarded of males. We are not sure but feel his previous owner was not too kind. 

Our trainer has suggested slow introductions to other dogs and also supervised play time at first to avoid any dominant tendencies during playtime. 

Tommy will be amazing for a single female owner. He will need a fenced yard to be able to have some fun. Daily exercise is a must. He will do best with an active adopter. 

Handsome Tommy has worked hard to become a better dog and hopefully someone's amazing pet. 

He is currently in Houston, but can be transported to the Pacific Northwest if adopted. Unfortunately at this time we had to cancel all meet and greets due to Covid 19 and had to keep all dogs in Houston until their adoptions. 

For an adoption application please go to www.springbranchrescue.org

animal.description:
Anna, Elsa, Kristoff... Olaf??? Arent you looking for me? Oh wait... thats only my namesake! Hi I am Sven, your local happy dog looking for my forever people! Im a high energy guy who loves to be around my humans. I must admit Im definitely a lap dog ... whether you feel 59 pounds is a lapdog or not is your opinion. I want to be your little shadow and will do anything for some whip cream. I need slow intros with other dogs but I really need a home with a confident furry friend to be my very own emotional support dog haha. I have a secret .. I am a bit of anxious guy and need a home where I have a lot of confidence and training to boost my reactions to the world. I will be furever grateful in your home!

Sven is a 5 year old, 59lb greyhound/boxer mix who is UTD and microchipped. Sven is learning leash work but is crate and housetrained. He needs a home with another dog who is calm and confident to help with his anxiety. He is GREAT with kids and loves to play dress up with his humans. He is currently in training through us to help his confidence and will continue training after adoption to ensure successful transition. 

Adoption requirements are as such:


	Another dog who is calm and confident 
	Leash reactivity experience 


Please note, Sven is part of Happy Trails Animal Rescues rehoming program. He has not been tested or evaluated and the information gathered is from the current owners personal statements regarding health and temperament. The owner is subject to placement outside of our organization. We cannot guarantee availability.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Fergus (formerly Rocky) came to us from a very bad situation in WV. He was shot at as a puppy and timid from that. Then, in his 'home,' he was bullied by the other dog in the household, and because of that was relegated to the garage. He has been with us for a bit and then was adopted, but he is not the right match for his current household (due to the other animals there)... This boy needs a home where he will be loved and where his family can provide for (and match) his needs. Fergus is very, very sweet with people - he is a love -- and will love you to pieces once he gets acquainted with you and feels comfortable. It just takes him a little time at first as he is timid upon first meeting - but he is a total love (sensitive and sweet) once he gets to know you. And he has NO people aggression whatsoever - NONE!As for other animals, Fergus has interacted fine with the female dogs in the household. But he can react quite negatively to some male dogs, and he is NOT at all good with cats. So we are seeking a home without any cats (or other small animals) and without male dogs. And, just to err on the side of caution, we are actually seeking an adult home where Fergus be the only animal in the household.Fergus is smart and is housetrained. He is also doing so much better on leash walking. But since he can be timid upon first meeting, we feel the best environment for him would be a home with a physically fenced yard.
If you are interested in considering adopting Fergus - to provide him a loving, caring, responsible home for his whole life - please register on our website, www.safeatlast.net (by clicking Register on the left-hand side of our homepage). Once you receive your password on your email account, please log back on to our website to complete the Safe at Last online adoption application (by clicking Forms/Applications on the left-hand side of our homepage). If, after preliminary review of your application, your home appears to be a good match, a volunteer will be in touch to commence the review process. Our process is very straightforward but does involve the phone interview, reference checks and a home assessment.
Approved adopters are required to go to Fergus's current home (in Preston Hollow NY, Schoharie County) to meet him and complete the adoption.
Finally, you must submit the Safe at Last online adoption application and be approved prior to meeting him. If you do not submit the adoption application, we cannot consider you.
Thank you for choosing to rescue and for your interest in Fergus.
NYS Rescue Registry No. RR 087. 2/1/21 9:19 PM

We have adoption events EVERY SATURDAY from 12-3 p.m. Please note that not all dogs can attend every event, so if you are interested in meeting a particular dog, please complete a no-obligation application on our website at http://www.muttloverescue.org/application.html OR write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

Upcoming adoption events:

Mutt Love Rescue is doing everything we can to ensure the health and safety of our volunteers and adopters while continuing our mission to find homes for as many dogs as possible.

Effective immediately, we will not be holding our weekly adoption events. Dogs available for adoption can be met by appointment only. Potential adopters should submit an online application at http://muttloverescue.org/application.html. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to let you know the next steps.

We are always desperate for foster homes, now more than ever. If you are interested in fostering during this difficult time, please complete an application... unless you are a previous adopter/foster, then you can just contact us via phone (703-988-2608) or email (adopt@muttloverescue.org) to tell us which dog you want to foster!

animal.description: Rocco is a rock star who already has so many fans! That's because he loves them back so much. This cuddly, affectionate boy gets so excited when he meets any new humans and he loves nothing more than being close to them. He'll lay his head in their laps, and roll over for all the belly rubs and cuddles he can get. This respectful and mostly calm big boy enjoys sleeping on the couch, and chewing on toys. Occasionally he'd like to do a zoomie (who doesn't), but he is recovering from two fractures in his hind legs, so he is postponing his antics until he is fully healed. He walks well on his leash, and he only pulls when he sees a pesky squirrel sticking his tongue out at him. He's a treat-motivated, housetrained boy who sleeps well in his crate, and answers to 'sit' and 'lay down.' Rocco has gotten along well with other dogs and should do well with kids. He is heartworm positive, but that just means he'll need a couple of months of rest during treatment, at APA!'s expense. Come meet him, he'll show you his belly and ask for rubs! You can also follow his silly antics on Instagram @roccothedog_apa.

animal.description: Billy is a sweet dog who is shy but affectionate once you earn his trust.  He holds his own with dogs and likes to run and play with everyone now that he has been here a while.  He likes to stand for treats, likes to eat and is very good with the dogs over food etc.  He likes to sleep with his humans,  loves being petted and belly rubs and paid attention to.   He gets through small holes in fences but it is to be with you and not run away although a very secure yard is important because when you leave he may follow.  He has a big personality for a tiny guy, loves to do silly things when he is feeling chipper .Not sure on cats, isnt that thrilled with children but Billy is not an aggressive dog.  UTD, chipped and fully vetted, Billy is ready for a home that will be playful and fun but in a gentle way.  Does that make sense?.  He should be with someone who will spend time with him.  He is tiny at less than 10 pounds and very cute. Smart too,  He is a very sweet dog and though he sports a white face he is only said by old owner to be 6...an active home is the best home for little Billy!

animal.description:
Our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit. If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

I'm TAHOE! I'm a nice, solid guy.  My approx. DOB is 2/23/2019 so I'm still a sweet young thing.  I'm 23.5" at my withers and a nice, solid 58 lbs. I didn't have a lot of experiences in my past life so I'm still learning to trust and completely enjoy myself.  The big dog in my former home used to pick on me so I'm a little nervous until I've been in a situation for awhile.  I like being with my daycare pack.  I'm still nervous getting into and out of cars - it's a little scary.   

I totally love my ball and will play with it as long as there's someone to throw it for me.  I'm somewhat adverse to scary situations.  I'm not going to make a good hunter but I'll be a wonderful hiking/running companion.  I'll do well with another well-trained, well-socialized dog in my new home to show me the ropes.

---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

I totally love my ball and will play with it as long as there's someone to throw it for me.  I'm somewhat adverse to scary situations.  I'm not going to make a good hunter but I'll be a wonderful hiking/running companion.  I'll do well with another well-trained, well-socialized dog in my new home to show me the ropes.

---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.
