animal.description:
Dunn was pulled from a shelter near Corpus Christi with his brother Brooks.  Dunn is the bigger of the pair.  At 10 months old, he already weighs 50 pounds and stands 18 inches tall.  A DNA test on his brother recently reported that his hound genes come from a Catahoula Leopard mixed with Great Pyremees.  He also has 16 % Super Mutt mixed in!!  Here is what his foster Dad has to say about this sweet boy!

What can I say about Dunn?  He is an amazing PUPPY in a DOG’s body.   He is very high energy.  He most certainly will need to be part of a pack and not a single dog.  He will not do well in an apartment.  He has to have a dog door.  I have never had to scoop indoor poop and I only had to clean up 3 puddles before he learned the dog door and that was in the first 24 hours in the house.    He is crate trained.  He still needs work to settle before he eats.  He uses a maze bowl to eat, because he is a CHOW HOUND!  
 
He is crated when we leave the house.  He’s going to need that for a while.  But this week we have been letting stay with us in the bedroom at night.  He would probably sleep in the bed with his people if he was allowed but our pack is too big.  That being said, he does not protest and sleeps on his pillows on the floor in the bedroom.  He comes and goes at will during the night. 
 
He plays all the time with the dogs.  He does really well.  He and sugar play tug of war all the time.  He acts like a gangly teenager.  He is LONG; all legs.  He doesn’t know his back legs will spring him forward yet to jump so he climbs  
 
He learned sit and stay and down, but he is still working on not taking food before he is told it’s his.   He can nose the table while you’re eating by just craning his neck, so we are working on teaching him boundaries. 
 
Dunn will be a wonderful addition to an active family with other dogs and kids to chase around!


If you are interested in adopting one of our dogs, THE FIRST STEP is to complete our adoption questionnaire. Please visit our website at www.HoustonBeagleRescue.org and follow the instructions on adoption.  Our regular adoption fee is $275; mixes are $200; special needs and senior dogs are $175; pups under 8 months are $300. The fee includes the spay/neuter, the vaccines, flea and heart worm preventative/treatment, a new leash/ collar/ rescue ID tag, microchip, and some training. Some dogs may have had additional vet care such as orthopedic surgeries, heart worm treatment or other procedures, but these extras will not affect their adoption fee. Donations to help with vetcare are always welcomed!

animal.description: Hi, my name is Oscar. I'm 14 years young, and I love playing fetch and treats. My eyes are a little hazy, but I still get around great, and I'm very spry. I love my bed and my kennel, and if you take me out regularly I'm very well potty trained. I don't know if I like other dogs, but bigger things darting past me scare me a little. I do have heartworms, but I'm on the slow kill treatment so I can be super healthy! I'm not very noisy at all unless someone I don't know comes into the house, and once my people let me know the visitor is okay, I calm down really quickly. Because I am a senior I'll need a little extra vet care, and I would appreciate a calm home with no boisterous kids. I hope that I can find a really great family soon, and thank you for considering me!

animal.description:
Meet Paxton! Pax is a 3 yr old  lab/mountain cur mix boy who weighs around 50 lbs. He is a social, happy guy who escaped from a high kill shelter and is doing great in his foster home. He has 2 foster hound siblings that he runs around and plays with, and he does ok with with resident cats as well. He is very smart, and although he loves to catch a scent and chase, he is learning to be called off of that. Paxton is by nature part of a pack, and this is where he will be happiest. We need his adoptive family to have at least one other, playful dog in the home (more would be fine as well!) and a fully fenced in yard so everyone can run around and play. Paxton will be respectful to an owner who can set boundaries and realizes that consistency is key. If you want to meet Mr. Pax, send us an application!    

Please only children 15 or older in the adoptive home. 

The adoption fee of $200 will include spay/neuter, microchip, age appropriate/required vaccinations, treatment for heartworm and any other necessary medical treatment to assure a healthy new pup for your family. Although we do the best to describe breed, since our pups all come from shelters we can make no guarantee. We can tell you that they are 100% RESCUED! If you are interested in adopting/meeting , please visit our website at www.starfishanimalrescue.com or you may complete the online adoption application on our Facebook Page https://www.facebook.com/starfishanimalrescue/app/134425496630143/?ref=page_internal Once you complete and submit your dog adoption application we will set up an appointment to meet this pup! *please note that we are a foster home based rescue and we do home visits as part of the adoption process - we are unable to adopt to families who live outside of the Chicago and surrounding suburbs. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description: Caillou Cuddles is a sweet and comical little dog. He is 13 yrs old but you would never know it by the way he acts. He loves to run, play with, and chase his foster brothers. Caillou does not like to be picked up, and he is very reserved when he first meets you, but give him his space and he will come to you when he is ready. When he gets to know you, he loves to be petted and have some lap time. When he is tired of playing he retires to his bed and rolls up in his blanket. After a short nap, he is refreshed and ready to play again. Caillou loves to eat but is not a food hog. He will not steal food from the other dogs but will wait politely until they are done and then approach their bowls to see if there are any leftovers. He will then lick the bowl clean to make sure he did not miss anything.I love the way he always has one ear up and one ear down-he looks like he is ready for takeoff but can’t get enough power to lift him up. Caillou is house trained, good with other dogs big and small. I have no cats or children but given his temperament I do not think there would be any problem, but given his age and quiet nature, I think he would do better in peaceful household without any young children. He has the run of the house when his foster mom leaves to run errands as he is non destructive. Caillou is patiently waiting for his forever home!

Newt is a sweet boy. He came to us from a backyard breeder with his daughter. They were kept in outdoor kennels so they will need to learn house manners. They are both heartworm positive and have started their treatment. 

FOSTER THROUGH HEARTWORM TREATMENT BIO (NEED TO START TREATMENT)

NTTS is placing me for Foster to ensure I can get into a home sooner than later and start learning what it means to be a loved house dog. You see I came to the rescue with heartworms and have to go through the treatment to kill them. They say it is long and expensive and I have to stay well rested and not stressed. Can you help me get through this treatment?? The nice people here will provide everything you need to take care of me! You just have to give me love and my medicine everyday! 

If you would like to learn more about heartworm treatment, please visit this webiste https://www.heartwormsociety.org/heartworms-in-dogs

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Ivan and his sister Ivy joined Last Hope all the way from Texas. They were born in a field on the side of the road, and lived as a family until good samaritan's were able to catch the dogs and bring them into rescue. Ivan has learned to trust people, but he still needs time and space to warm up to strangers. He will thrive in a home with another confident dog that is playful and outgoing. He LOVES toys, especially soft and squeaky rubber ones. Ivan is also very treat motivated, even if he's nervous he will take treats, so he will be a super star in obedience classes and this will help to grow his confidence! Ivan will require a home with a physical fence, given that he is a fearful and could be a flight risk. He has not been introduced to cats or children, he could potentially be a fit with a dog savvy cat and older children that can recognize a fearful dog.

Ivan's adoption fee is $250 and includes his neuter, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives PLUS a free obedience course at Cedar Run in Hiawatha. Last Hope requires that all animals be altered, current on vaccinations and preventatives and kept as indoor pets only. Our adoption process includes reference and vet checks, a home visit and background check.

animal.description:
Barracuda came from a backyard breeder. He was chained outside the entire first year of his life. He has been in my rescue since mid September, has been viewed 598 times on petfinder with not a pinch of interest. I have no idea why!! He's a BEAUTIFUL year and a half old sweetheart. He's dog friendly, kid friendly, and is easy to train. He is a people pleaser. He will do anything for a kiss. He's constantly smiling and is a mega mood booster! He loves the hammock with his human, long walks, and the leaf blower! He's a great cuddler and matches the energy of his family. He has A LOT of energy and loves to stay on the move...but will settle down for a snack and a movie. If a dog or child is shy around him, he lays down or rolls over to make sure he doesn't come off as intimidating. He has a small amount of separation anxiety. He is not destructive if left alone for short periods but he does get depressed quickly when lonely. He would love a larger sized family so that he can have extra attention without having to be clingy. But ultimately he will bond with whoever loves him the most! 
More Pictures and videos can be found at:  linktr.ee/lcpitbullrescue

animal.description:
Jingle is available for adoption at the Tacoma Humane Society. 

Hi, my name is JINGLE and I would love to meet you. I am a Spayed Female Pit Bull Terrier and Chow Chow. The shelter staff think I am about 2 years and 7 months old. I have been at the shelter since Aug 07, 2020.

Jingle spent the past month in a wonderful foster home where we learned so many things about her silly and funny personality!
Jingle is a cuddly clown in the house. She loves to play with her toys, chew on her bones, and snuggle with her people. She enjoys some good zoomies in the yard but that`s pretty much enough for her to settle down in the couch with her peeps. Her foster mom reports that Jingle does fine sleeping in her crate but would MUCH rather spoon in bed with someone! 

This sweet girl came to the shelter as a stray, so her history before foster is unknown. Jingle enjoys going for walks and runs but she tends to be very excitable and vocal when seeing other animals. Her foster home was working on this behavior and she is slowly coming along but will need the help of a qualified trainer with her new family. But it is easy enough to find places where there are no other dogs for walks or she is pretty content to run and play in a fenced yard. 

Jingle would love a home with a big fenced yard where she can run and play as much as she wants. Jingle is looking for a home with Teens or Adults who would be comfortable interacting with a bouncy dog. At this point she does need to be the ONLY PET in the home. Due to Jingle needing her own space from other dogs, apartment living is not appropriate. This girl wants her own backyard to run and hangout with her family. Jingle is ready and willing to jump right into some private training with a qualified trainer who can help her work on her leash reactivity.

animal.description:
Andreas – Earlier in May of this year, Animal Services responded to a call and found a dog ‘stuck and tied’ under a house with a rope left in place so long it had grown into the 6 month old puppy’s neck and become horribly infected.   The owner, already in custody for unrelated charges, was charged with cruelty to animals and remained in custody.  The pet was removed and treated by SPCA Alliance of North Carolina.   Since SPCA NC does not place any pets, this fellow was pulled by GCCR who also provided financial support for Andreas’ medical.    Andreas continued his medical treatment with Godbey Creek and today has a clean bill of health and well as love, attention and basic training!  

While Andreas still sports a few scars from his embedded collar ordeal, you would never know this sweet fellow was abused.  See photos.   From his handsome coat to his healthy attitude to his playful antics, this very good natured 10 month old will make a wonderful companion for an experienced pet owner.    Andreas lives to run like the wind and, while he gets along very well with other dogs, the only thing on his mind is expending his energy and playing.    He has begun to learn some basic manners but needs an experienced pet owner who will maintain his training and provide him plenty of love and exercise.   Andreas is completely crate trained, has gone over two weeks without any accidents indoors and is well on his way to learning basic house manners.   This rambunctious fellow walks beautifully on the leash and is just a great dog.   Andreas has never met a stranger!   

The successful owner of Andreas will provide this deserving pet an indoor – outdoor life, have a fenced in yard because you cannot possibly expend Andreas’ energy, have time to play with this handsome fellow AND have experience teaching pets basic commands.   An ideal situation would be that Andreas would have a playmate of equal size to help him release his energy!   Due to his prey drive, a home with cats is not a good fit.  

For more information about Andreas OR to schedule an appointment to meet this great guy, phone 336.972.4511 OR 828.302.6175.

animal.description:
GAINSEVILLE, TEXAS ***NEEDS FOSTER or ADOPT ***

Meet Adele!  She was just pulled from a high kill shelter and is in need of either a FOSTER, FOSTER TO ADOPT or ADOPTIVE home.

Adele is a beautiful Anatolian Shepherd mix. Adele's estimated DOB is November 2019. She currently weighs 70 lbs but is still growing.  Adele is spayed, microchipped, fully vaccinated, heartworm negative and free of parasites.

Adele is still just a (big) puppy!  She is very playful and energetic as you would expect a puppy to be.
Adele's perfect home would be a home with another young, large to medium sized dog who loves to play as much as she does.  Her favorite pastime is romping and wrestling with her foster brothers.

No small dogs or kitties, please!

She is an excellent watch dog and alerts to sounds and people.She will bark at visitors but settles down and is welcoming when she is told that it’s alright. 

Adele loves to go on car rides.  She is a good traveler. She is working on leash manners and basic commands but will still need more training. She is housebroken and crate trained.

Adele likes to have her own space to eat in as she does not like to share her food with the other dogs.

Best suited home will have:
A young, large to medium size playful dog
No small dogs or cats
6 foot privacy fence

For more information please email asdrescue@gmail.com

Transport: **PLEASE READ CAREFULLY**

If you are within 1,000 miles, we can usually help with transport using volunteer drivers (depending on the route/availability of volunteers).

If you live farther than 1,000 miles, we can still assist, however, the adopting party will need to drive any mileage over 1,000 miles.  

For example, if you live 1200 miles away, you would have to drive 200 miles out.

Not sure how far away you are?  Please ask google, she will tell you!

animal.description:
Prince weighs around 60lbs and is around 10 y/o. He is very friendly with all people and walks nicely on a tension collar or slip lead. He's fully vetted, graduated from training BOOT CAMP - and ready for a home. Prince is the perfect gentleman and a total LOVE and so VERY SPECIAL - you will fall in love instantly. Won't you come and meet him?
This sweet Prince showed up on the doorstep of his foster mom wearing only a pink collar that said 'I'm Prince, I don't bite. Please love me.' He just sat quietly by the back door, hoping someone would let him in. Tragically, his foster mom now has cancer and he must move on quickly.
Prince is gentle, friendly and relatively calm for a young dog. He approaches in a submissive way and seems to always be wagging his tail. All he needs now is a home to hang his collar in.
Age: 10 y/o
Weight: 60 lbs
Temperament: Good with some dogs (prefers females), cats and kids
Vetting: Neutered, up-to-date on vaccines and heartworm negative
Apply today!
Dog Adoption Application(bit.ly/DH-Adoption)Dog Foster Application(bit.ly/DH-Fosters)

Prince is gentle, friendly and relatively calm for a young dog. He approaches in a submissive way and seems to always be wagging his tail. Prince understands commands like "sit", "down" and "stay" -- though not consistent, with a little training he would be on track. All he needs now is a home to hang his collar, hopefully a new one, message no longer needed. He's even masculine enough to wear pink!

Prince has been vaccinated and neutered, but has received a diagnosis of 'light' heartworms and is currently undergoing treatment. He will soon be 100% healthy but is ready for adoption (or foster) ASAP. Please contact Debbie at deb923@bellsouth.net with questions or if your interested in adopting, complete an application from Doggie Harmony > Forms and send it to deb923@bellsouth.net and jamie@doggieharmony.org.

My name is Simon and I am a Great Pyrenees mix. Maybe I have Aussie in me or Brittany Spaniel. I came into rescue when my owners that cared for me very much had to move and could not take me with them. I'm an energetic guy and would like an active owner. My foster dad says I'm great on a leash. I love being in the fields with him running with my nose to the ground. When I'm on a long lead I keep my eye on my foster dad and come back to check in. When meeting new people I'm a little nervous at first but I warm up quickly. Then I'll take all the loves and pets I can get. I love to play fetch and will play all day long! I would enjoy playing with another dog in my home after a slow introduction and I am just fine with cats and horses. I will come to you microchipped, neutered, up to date on vaccinations, and up to date on heartworm and flea/tick preventatives. 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved, you must also pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. Children in my home must be at least 10 years of age. I can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, and Arkansas. My rescue is able to transport me to those states. If you would like to give me a Furever home, please fill out an application on my rescue's website. 

Being fostered in Holden, MO

animal.description:
"Forever A Southern Gentle Pyr." You won't be in better company than with Jingo, a handsome six-year-old Great Pyrenees. He is a popular guy at the dog park and likes to supervise the other dogs to ensure there are no disagreements while he leans on his admirers for pets.

We don't know much about his life before the Great Pyrenees Rescue Society rescued him from a Texas animal shelter after found as a stray in a country field.

We know that Jingo is affectionate and can never get tired of being talked to and petted. He will affectionately ask you for a tummy rub by tucking his front paws into your body. Jingo is house trained, crate trained, and trustworthy enough to have the run of the house as he is not destructive. He behaves on car rides by laying down quietly.

Older Pyrs like to sleep in and take naps throughout the day, and sometimes Jingo won't get up to go potty outside when asked. He will instead roll on his back for tummy rubs or occasionally pretend to be asleep. Pyrs have a sense of humor you gotta love. He has a slight hip dysplasia, a manageable condition with lifestyle modifications, weight control, limited exercise and joint supplements.

Jingo would thrive in a home with adults, no small children, no cats, and no stairs. Jingo would benefit from a daily walk or hike in his new home and a fenced yard to play in with a semi active resident canine. If you have a place in your home and your heart for Jingo, please complete an application.

All dogs and puppies require VISIBLE fencing

Adoption Fee: $300. (Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225). Adoption applications can be found on our website at https://www.greatpyreneesrescuesociety.org/.

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer!

animal.description: You won't find a sweeter dog than Sofee! She wants nothing more than to please her people. Sofee is about 4 years old and has gorgeous brindle markings. We have her listed as a Lab and American Staffordshire Terrier mix but she is likey a mix of many breeds. She is gentle and has done well with all the people she meets. She is a fast learner, but she likes to take her time and think about it first. She needs a household able to set up and maintain boundaries for her but then she quickly fits right in once she knows the rules of the house. She is housetrained, sleeps through the night in her crate, and has done well when left home alone in a room for a few hours. Sofee likes to chase after balls and goes for short walks but is more of a couch potato and prefers to lounge around with her humans. She is happy to get her mental stimulation through toys and puzzles with the occasional burst of zoomies. Those zoomies don't last long though before she switches gears and decides to take a nap by the pool instead. She is still working on her leash manners out and about on walks and would love a patient family able to continue her training. Sofee loves her humans so much that she doesn't like to share attention with other dogs and will need to be the only dog in her home. She's not a dog park or dog beach kind of girl and would much rather play with her people than have anything to do with other dogs. So far, she has been good with the two cats at her current foster home although if they run by her, sometimes she thinks that means they want to play. When she first came to Labs and More, Sofee was missing hair and had angry, red irritated skin. She received the medical care she needed and now her coat is smooth with those brindle tiger stripe markings really showing through and all her fur has grown back. She just needs to be on a special food to maintain her coat, but no longer needs daily medications. If you are looking for a companion who gives hugs and kisses and is all smiles Sofee might be the girl for you. If you are interested in meeting Sofee, your first step would be to submit an adoption application on our website. If you are already approved with an adoption coach or have adopted from us before, reach out to your coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description: Dash is a playful boy who can't decide what he loves best - cuddling up on top of his human friends or curling up under his blankets. For sure, he wants to be as close to his people as possible, with lots of snuggling. Then he'll stare at them and paw until they lift a blanket so he can snuggle under it. This rambunctious boy also loves runs in the backyard, and going for the leash walks he does so well. He can have a little anxiety about strange things he sees, but he would like to meet and play with other dogs he sees. And he's done well on playdates with other APA! dogs his size. Back home, he loves playing tug-o-war and playing with his ball and stuffy toy. Then he's ready for his naps, preferably under his blankets. He is a smart boy who comes when called, and answers to sit, stay, down, shake and free. And he does very well in his crate, and also can roam the house nicely, doing fine when home alone. Plus, he's very well house-trained. This loving cuddle bug would thrive in a home with a backyard to run in, preferably with a wooden privacy fence that would keep him from seeing those strange things he sometimes fears. He may do best as the only pet, but has done well with other pups. And he loves all adults and responsible teenagers, especially those who can help him relax. Come meet him - offer him a blanket and he'll follow you home.

animal.description:
MEET COCO!

Coco is three years old and weighs about 45lbs. She's a big personality in a compact size. Coco is a fun dog to have around. You'll catch her zooming around the yard, romping with her doggie friends, and chasing her tail. She is best with a male companion (large or small) and is way too interested for a cat home. Coco appreciates cuddles with her humans and is a great car buddy. 

Coco has a clean bill of health. You may notice the bump on her cheek. Coco has visited multiple veterinarians and they all concur that the bump is from a previous trauma. They also indicated that because it doesn't bother her. They don’t recommend unnecessary cosmetic surgery. She has had a biopsy and confirmation that it is a fatty tumor and not cancer. Though we will never know what Coco experienced before rescue, we know her future forever family will love her just the way she is. 

Coco is a courtesy post and all placement decisions will be made by Coco’s guardian. If you are interested in meeting  please fill out an application at our website www.gobeyondrescue.org/adopt and we will forward your information.

He really would like to play but most of the dogs in his foster home are old and have no interest. However, he's respectful of them and gets along with everyone.
If you're looking for an extremely sweet best friend and companion to share life's adventures with and already have a nice doggy who would love a playmate, please submit an adoption application for Sam Houston. animal.description:
Anyone who has met her has used the words "angel" and "lovebug". Hennessy loves people, pets, belly rubs and treats (like most dogs).

She's house trained, crate trained, she knows "sit", never really barks (unless to play with you or at other dogs), easy to bathe, and walk around the neighborhood.

After a walk, Hennessy loves to people watch and admire cars that drive by.  Hennessy lives off of the energy of the people around her - she can be playful in tug-o-war or lowkey in a lazy afternoon. When she gets excited, she will do a little "aroo" to get you to play and jump around. In the evening, she'll go to her doggy bed parked next to your bed and sleep for a straight 8 hours.

Hennessy does not like other dogs so would need to be the only animal in the household. This queen doesn’t like to share her people. But she does amazing with people and children! 

Due to her poorly cropped ears, Hennessy does require some general maintenance to prevent infections. Additionally, as with most meatballs, she has some skin sensitivity and allergies, but nothing that requires any extra care for now.

You may read more about our adoption policies and procedures at www.truenorthrescue.org. Please submit a complete application on our website - meet and greets are only scheduled with approved applicants. Please be sure to answer every question as thoughtfully as you can, this will help your chances. Incomplete applications will not be reviewed, and we unfortunately can not contact all applicants to inquire about missing information.

Do not email through Petfinder because we won't be able to answer. Please email adopt.truenorthrescue@gmail.com to check on the status of your application. All applications can take anywhere from 24-72 hours to be processed and only approved applicants will be contacted.

If a dog is listed here on Petfinder, they are still available. Please don't email just to ask if they're available - they are! With the high volume of emails we receive daily, it is not guaranteed that we can reply to every inquiry. As a fully volunteer run rescue, we make every effort to reply in a timely fashion, but please allow 24-48 hours for a response.

We strive to have accurate and up to date bios, and regularly check in with our fosters to ensure we are providing the most relevant information. If there is no mention of a health or behavioral concern, then it means we have not been informed of one!

"Paris is always a good idea," and we happen to agree about our Paris! This pretty girl happens be deaf, and it doesn't seem like she has had the chance to consistently work on hand signals so far. She is a sensitive lady, and can be easily startled and unsure in new places - so she would do best in a quieter, patient home that will take the time to help her learn a language she can understand! So far, this darling girl has been quite demure and sweet. She checks in regularly with her person on walks, which is a great start for learning sign language! She seems to be housebroken, and so far she has walked well on leash. Paris will likely need careful intros with other dogs - being deaf, she can't pick up on vocal cues from other animals. With a little love, patience and learning, Paris will be the good girl we know her to be! Paris is around 3 years old and weighs 56 lbs.

Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

animal.description:
***Zadie is only available through our Foster to Adopt Program***

Hi, my name is Zadie! Thanks for taking the time to look at me. 

As you can see I'm a very pretty lady. I'm a sweet girl who came up here from the south. My life down there was far from the best. But some kind people came to save me! I was so scared when got here, to tell you the truth, I am still pretty scared and I need you to understand that but someone great like you, I'm sure you will. It's not my fault I'm scared and my foster mom says I'm a very brave girl. My first few days with her I was too afraid to move at all but now cuddling with her and my foster doggie brother is my favorite! When things get too scary (like loud sounds outside or new people coming over) I love my kennel as it is my safe place, I also love under my foster mom's bed. I'm shy to meeting new people but after a while I'll slowly come out and give some sniffs and kisses. Men kind of scare me and I warm up to women faster. All I want is to give love and to get pets in return. 

And toys! Do you know what toys are? I'm just learning and wow are they awesome! I love dogs and cats! My foster mom says I play a little too rough with her cat so maybe one wouldn't be best in my house. I'm working on learning commands and my foster mom says I am very smart. I am still working on potty training. Sometimes outside is just so scary still, but I'm close to getting there. 

The vet says I have this thing called heart worm. Don't worry it will go away with treatment and time. I am such a tough girl! I hope this doesn't make you over look me. I would love if you would give me a chance. All I want is a loving forever family. Maybe that's you?

FOSTER TO ADOPT:
Zadie is Heartworm positive and is in the middle of her Heartworm treatment. This treatment takes about 3 months with 3-5 appointments at our vets in Minnetonka. After the treatment series is completed, a heartworm test is done a month later and repeated in the months following until a negative test result is achieved. A negative result can take up to 2-9 months after treatment. During the treatment and until the test result is negative, she will need to make sure her heart rate is not elevated due to high energy play or exercise. Zadie is only available through the Foster to Adopt Program at this time. The foster to adopt commitment will be for an ADOPTION but will be actually fostering until she is cleared with a negative Heartworm test result, which at that time, we will make the adoption official. All of the medical expenses will be paid for by the rescue while she is in a foster to adopt home. Food, kennel, grooming and other supplies will be provided by the foster in the foster to adopt program. 

--------------------------------------------


All our Warrior Dogs will have all age appropriate medical care and vaccines, a microchip, and spay/neuter before adoption unless age is a factor with a puppy younger than 6-12 months at the time of adoption. If that is the case, the spay/neuter will be covered in the adoption fee and the owner will be responsible to have the procedure completed at a Warrior Dog Rescue Veterinarian at the appropriate time.

Please note that the majority of our dogs in rescue are from shelters where they have been found as strays or abandoned. Their breed description is based on our very best educated guess based on physical characteristics and their dispositions. If they came to our rescue as an owner surrender, the breed description will be listed as provided by the previous owner.

Adoption Fee - $450

To apply for this pup, please submit an Adoption Application at http://warriordogrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application/

Soulful like the ocean waves!

Hey guys, my name is Windansea and I am about 6 years old, male German Shepherd mix. I am a big boy at about 70 lbs and have been neutered already. I was splashing about on the streets of TJ and TAP rescued me to find me my forever home. I have thrived at my foster home and filled up nicely with 3-4 small meals. I am learning house manners and I am a master at going to bathroom now! I always let my fam know and never have any accidents. I am still picking up on leash training and positive reinforcement is working so well! My treat motivation has helped me learn commands too!

I have had some niggle-wiggles while walking and I recently saw a very nice vet. They mentioned that I may have some ibuprofens to take for a long time. I have some delicate joints and supplements will help. A bit of swimming and physiotherapy will also help me stay light on my feet. I don't need surgery, just a bit of joint management to stay happier!

I am a mellow and chilled out guy and I love to be around my family. I am friendly, amicable and totally not jumpy! I have so much sweetness in my heart and I love to give my people all the love in my heart. I enjoy going on walks and I am getting better on the leash. I am an easy-maintenance guy and just company and attention makes me happy. I am friendly with every person I meet, kids or adults. With doggos, I am a lil selective and I prefer slow introductions to figure out how we'll get along. I have a feeling, I will prefer to be the only pet in the home.

I'd love to be with a family that has a lot of love to share! I would like to be the only doggo of the house for ultimate attention. If you think we are a great match, wave at me! My adoption fee is $350 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

Cherry has your typical Boxer temperament - constant wiggles, bouncing, lots of affection, never a bad day, & her little nub tail never stops!

animal.description:
Meet Panza, a female who we're guessing is Red Heeler mixed with Golden Retriever.   An Australian Cattle Dog, or Heeler , is a breed of herding dog developed in Australia for driving cattle over long distances across rough terrain in all weather.  The breed comes in two main colors, one of which is the Red Heeler, i.e. Panza.  Everyone knows Goldens.  Panza has clearly had someone who cared for her before: she rides very well in a car and she already knows "sit", "shake", "down", "rollover" and she'll "stay" for the most part.  Whatever situation caused Panza to end up in a shelter has not resulted in her having any ill will toward humans - she loves people and wants to be with them always.  Panza's estimated DOB is 9/1/2017 which means that she is fully grown and out of the "puppy" stage.  That does not mean, however, that she is a couch potato.  As the description implies, Heelers are very smart and trainable, obedient, loyal, with a lot of energy.  She is extremely affectionate, has a very playful nature with humans and, being a dog bred to work hard, she can keep up with just about anyone.   Being so smart, Heelers need both mental and physical stimulation to be happy dogs.  They, and presumably Panza, may nip at people and other dogs to guide them.  So, a home with small children may not be the best choice.  She would be best with no children or teenagers. Panza has plenty of energy that she needs to use.  She'll be a good running companion if asked.  From what we've seen, Panza is not a fan of other dogs and would do best as an only dog. Panza seems to have great house manners and does not tear up her bedding or toys.  She's ready for a home!  

If you are interested in Panza, please fill out an application here:
https://www.parkvilleshelter.com/adoption-application

animal.description:
Meet Hercules!

This handsome boy came in through city impound so we don't know a ton about him. We do believe that he is a Great Pyrenees/Husky mix. We do know that he was a stray in Spencer who had been hit with a car. He is healing up nicely and is ready to find his forever home! He does still have some swelling in one of his paws, which you can see in some of the pictures, but he is on medicine to help with that! Herc doesn't seem to be a big fan of bigger male dogs, but he LOVES female dogs of any size! He does seem interested in cats, but it appears as if he wants to play, so playful cats is a plus!

Update: Our boy Hercules has returned to us. He was in a special situation that just wasn't the best fit for him or the family. He is an absolute goofball who would do great with someone who is willing to help him learn! His previous owner, who wants the best for this sweet boy, has written a history from what he had learned from Herc while he was with him. If you are interested in Herky and would like to read that please let us know, it will give you a great look into what Herky is looking for and what he will need in a forever home. The previous owner is also willing to talk about Hercules to anyone who is interested in him and might have a few questions, he truly wants what is best for Hercules! 

Hercules is up to date on his vaccinations and is neutered. His adoption fee is $350. For any other questions or to request an adoption application please email Donna at djerickson1@hotmail.com.

animal.description:
During these uncertain times, we are still doing adoptions. To help keep all parties safe we will not be holding adoption events or meeting in any store locations. All meet and greets will be private and held at an outdoor location in Lake Elmo.

Please request an application via email or by a Petfinder request. For more information on the rescue, what the fee includes, surgery program, etc please see the home page.

Adoption fee: $450 cash or card only (There is a $10 fee to use a card) NO CHECKS

Age: 8-9 weeks
DOB Approx. 7-23-20?
Gender: Male
Altered: NO- surgery is included in the fee, please see information below
Breed: Mixed breed
Approx Weight Now:  6-9 pounds
Approx Weight Grown: 45-65 pounds complete guess as we do not know parents 
Dog-friendly: Yes
Cat-friendly: Yes
Kid-friendly: Yes
House Trained: No
Crate-Trained: No
Benefit From Formal Training: All puppies benefit from training
Energy level: Moderate
History: Surrendered to the shelter- have no info on where they came from or their parents. 

Note From the Foster:
These are normal healthy typical puppies. They like to run, play, and get into things. They will need training. Do not forget puppies are a lot of work but with work comes great joy.  We do not know their parents so their size is a complete guess for us. Average puppies this size tend to be in the 45-70 pound range. 


SURGERY INFORMATION:
I will be getting fixed on 10-8. If you adopt me before this date you will be required to bring me to this appointment. We will not hold them until their surgery date or reschedule any surgery that is already scheduled. This appointment can be changed at the need of the surgery facility with short notice.

The surgery appointment is in Golden Valley.
Drop off is 7:30 and pick up can be any time between 1-4. They will contact you when surgery is complete and the dog is ready to be picked up

University of Minnesota @ Animal Humane Society Veterinary Services Building
845 Meadow Ln. N.
Golden Valley, MN 55422

Currently, our surgical programs have opened back up. Since we cannot guarantee that they will not close due to a COVID outbreak we do need to protect ourselves. If this happens and we cannot get your dog in for surgery at our program facility you will have to follow the guidelines of our COVID-19 spay and neuter contract. 

 If this contract is in place due to a COVID outbreak in the facility.  Adopters will be required to fix on their own, at their own expense, by the age of 6 months old. If they are already 6 months old at the time of adoption then you will have 4 weeks to have them fixed. If proof is provided within 2 weeks of the completed surgery an up to $100 refund for the cost of surgery ONLY will be returned to the adopter. It is not to exceed the cost of the surgery only.  We will also not return any money if your dog is fixed as part of a wellness plan. You must inform us if you have scheduled your dog for surgery at your own vet if under this contract.

animal.description:
Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Charlie (aka Charles)

Dog's Approximate Age: 10.5 years

Gender: Male

Dog's Size: Pocket Boxer (under 50lbs as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 48 pounds

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Don't know yet

Good with kids?: Yes, all ages

Any medical issues?: Tooth Abscess (Under going surgery soon to fix this.)
Dermatological Issues (Currently on meds and improving all ready.)

Crate trained?: Yes

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: No

9/16/20: Hi. I'm Charlie. I'm a very distinguished man. I am enjoying retirement a lot. My favorite things to do are lounge around on my dog bed, people watch, be petted and wander around outside! I do not run or jump. I don't bark. I don't chew. I currently live with two large boxers and I don't mind them. I don't mind them at all. I prefer dogs aren't in my face. I will never seek out another dog. If you're looking for a quite and low maintenance companion, THATS ME! I really want a family who will pet me and let me rest when I want. I am very well house trained, I sleep through the night without asking to go potty. I will let you know when I have to go. I'm a food grazer so I won't gobble down food, it will last me all day. I'm a great old dog wanting to relax in your home with YOU!

_____________________________________________________________________________

Come visit carolinaboxerrescue.org to learn more about me and see more pictures. Learn about our adoption process too!

_____________________________________________________________________________

animal.description:
These two guys are the very best of friends and we would love for them to find a home together.  Both have been in our adoption program since 2018.  They really want a home with a fenced in yard because they love to lay out in the sunshine during good weather. However, they don't want to be "outside only" dogs.  They want to be able sleep inside at night, be inside during bad weather, and of course for cuddles and snuggles.  
Beau's DOB is 7/13/2011 and he weighs 39 pounds.  He came into rescue after being hit by a car and had paralysis in his back legs. After lots of rest and rehabilitation he recovered and is now walking.  Beau is easygoing and loves to bask in the sunshine.  He takes treats gently and walks nicely on a leash.  He likes to play with Chato and Chato seems to know that Beau can't roughhouse.  Beau is looking for a home with a gentle lifestyle with his best friend Chato.  Beau will also need to stay at a healthy weight.  Beau is current on vaccines, neutered, on heartworm and flea/tick prevention, and microchipped.  If you are interested in Beau and Chato, go to www.tysorvet.net and click on the adoption tab.  There you will find a link to the adoption application. 
 Chato's DOB is 7/16/2017 and he weighs 41 pounds.  He was originally rescued by a rescue organization but developed a urinary tract infection and they surrendered him to our adoption program.  Chato is a very sweet low key pup.  If you are lucky he will curl up his top lip to give you a grin.  Chato takes treats gencly and walks nicely on a leash.  He loves his best friend, Beau.   Chato loves being out in the backyard with Beau and will often get "the zoomies" when you engage him in play.  His coat is a lovely white with some patches of light brown.  He will benefit from regular brushing.  Chato is current on vaccines, neutered, on heartworm and flea/tick prevention, and microchipped.  If you are interested in Beau and Chato go to www.tysorvet.net and click on the adoption tab.  There you will find a link to the adoption application.

animal.description:
These two guys are the very best of friends and we would love for them to find a home together.  Both have been in our adoption program since 2018.  They really want a home with a fenced in yard because they love to lay out in the sunshine during good weather. However, they don't want to be "outside only" dogs.  They want to be able sleep inside at night, be inside during bad weather, and of course for cuddles and snuggles.  
Beau's DOB is 7/13/2011 and he weighs 39 pounds.  He came into rescue after being hit by a car and had paralysis in his back legs. After lots of rest and rehabilitation he recovered and is now walking.  Beau is easygoing and loves to bask in the sunshine.  He takes treats gently and walks nicely on a leash.  He likes to play with Chato and Chato seems to know that Beau can't roughhouse.  Beau is looking for a home with a gentle lifestyle with his best friend Chato.  Beau will also need to stay at a healthy weight.  Beau is current on vaccines, neutered, on heartworm and flea/tick prevention, and microchipped.  If you are interested in Beau and Chato, go to www.tysorvet.net and click on the adoption tab.  There you will find a link to the adoption application. 
 Chato's DOB is 7/16/2017 and he weighs 41 pounds.  He was originally rescued by a rescue organization but developed a urinary tract infection and they surrendered him to our adoption program.  Chato is a very sweet low key pup.  If you are lucky he will curl up his top lip to give you a grin.  Chato takes treats gencly and walks nicely on a leash.  He loves his best friend, Beau.   Chato loves being out in the backyard with Beau and will often get "the zoomies" when you engage him in play.  His coat is a lovely white with some patches of light brown.  He will benefit from regular brushing.  Chato is current on vaccines, neutered, on heartworm and flea/tick prevention, and microchipped.  If you are interested in Beau and Chato go to www.tysorvet.net and click on the adoption tab.  There you will find a link to the adoption application.

animal.description:
We first met Kiko in the Wichita Animal Shelter. She was a terrified dog abandoned as part of an eviction, left behind like an old couch or broken appliance. The sweetest soul that begged for someone to save her life. So we did.... We got Kiko out of the shelter, and she has already captured the hearts of Beauties volunteers. Kiko is safe and she is loved. Her fosters say is very sweet and mellow. She is still fearful. She is slowly learning to trust and we know she will come out of her shell with time and patience.

But Kiko's story is even more heartbreaking than we initially thought. We knew she had an odd issue with her shoulder, but had no idea what was wrong. She has been to see a vet for consultation at Northridge, which revealed she has a luxating scapula. This is not a common injury for a dog, and we don't know how long she has suffered from this injury. Kiko will need surgery to repair her injured shoulder.

animal.description:
Jepson is a 4 year old, 78 pound Great Pyrenees mix looking for his new home.  Jepson came to us along with 12 other Great Pyrenees mixes from a rather unfortunate hoarding situation. He was riddled with mange on arrival and in an attempt to treat it, someone poured a chemical solvent on his back, permanently scarring the top of his back between his shoulders and above his tail. He is now perfectly healthy and, despite this background, this dog loves people.

Jepson is also locally famous as a dog that defended one of our employees who was walking him when someone tried to do a snatch and grab of her into a van. Jepson was not having it and they backed off and drove away. This is what this breed does and he did his job exceedingly well. Jepson is friendly to all unless you threaten someone he loves. 

Jepson is best as an only dog as he does not want to share with other dogs anymore. He is also a no cat dog.  He is social, happy and friendly with people and he is good with kids over 10. He needs a home with people who understand the Great Pyrenees breed and with a fenced yard. He would love a sofa to crash on and he has zero understanding of why if you have two hands to pet him with, that they could possibly be occupied with anything other than petting him. This dog is going to make a fantastic pet for the right home.


If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/ then email mandy@bigfluffydogs.com. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description:
***Special Needs home needed for this deaf squishy*** 

This 3-4 year old squishy is looking for the perfect home where he will be loved and cherished for all of his cute quirks and special needs. What does Boulder need you ask... Well let me tell you! 

1. Someone that loves to play fetch and will play with him daily! 
2. A fenced in yard to play fetch in! 
3. An all adult home with no other pets that is willing to put him away when unknown people come over. Intros to new people can be done, but they need to be slow and involve lots of treats! 
4. Someone that knows that some deaf dogs have fear based reactivity to unknown stimuli and is willing to keep this boy and everyone else around him safe. 
5.. A strong leader that will set boundaries. No pushovers for this guy!
6. Someone that will show him the world. He loves to walk in different places and will follow at your heel. He also loves the water! 
7. A patient owner that will start out slow with him while he gets comfortable in a new environment. 
8. Someone that will appreciate all of his quirks! He has lots of adorable habits like nursing on his beds. It is adorable until you have to wash the slobbery bed! 

Boulder is currently living at our adoption center where he is beloved by the staff and volunteers that care for him. He gets to go on field trips to parks, lakes, and friends houses to play fetch. As much as we love Boulder and Boulder loves us, he is ready to find his forever home where he can play lots of fetch! Read more about him below: 

Hi, my name is Boulder and I am the squishiest goof ball in the triangle! I am the kind of dog that would love nothing more than to play fetch with you allllll day in the backyard, then flop over for some belly rubs! If I know you and trust you, we will be the bestest of friends! Because I am deaf, I am in need of a patient foster/adopter that understands that I must have a routine in order to thrive. I do have some fear aggression, but all that goes away when I am introduced to new people/situations properly and systematically. If someone sneaks up on me when I am not expecting it, I get quite spooked. The staff here has compared me to Scooby Doo, but I am much more handsome than he was... They tell me it's because I'm a scaredy cat... I wish I could get all those Scooby snacks like he did! 

I love to go for walks, but am quite the strong boy and I do better when on a harness. I also get excited when I see other dogs, so a backyard is preferable so walking is a luxury and not a must. I am searching for a calm, adult only home that will love me and cherish me for the big doof that I am. The Dog Program Manager here has really put emphasis on me being in a structured environment with a clear routine. She has seen the absolute best and the worst of me, and is certain that I will make the right household extremely happy. It is hard to not smile when you look at me goof trotting around and flopping over when I am protesting something. If you are an experienced dog person, that is willing to work with Second Chance to ensure that I am set up to succeed, and you have lots of patience and love to give, then I may be the boy for you! I am currently only available for the foster to adopt since I have some behavioral special needs. In the meantime, I would love to be in a foster home rather than in a room at the adoption center. If you are interested in fostering me, or would like to learn more about me, please contact the Dog Program Manager at laura@secondchancenc.org. Thank you!!!

animal.description:
Male Coonhound-Foxhound Mix

Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Approximate date of birth: 08/28/2017

Weight: 53 lbs

Children: Yes 

Dogs: Yes 

Cats: Yes


AJ is a super sweet and affectionate boy who loves running around and following his nose when he catches a scent in our fields. AJ is very friendly with other dogs as long as they don't try to take his things. He doesn't like to share and is a bit possessive when it comes to his valuables. So his adopter will need to be mindful of this resource guarding behavior and work with him on it. This behavior is quite common in dogs who have been in the shelter system for a long time or come from very difficult backgrounds, like not knowing where or when their next meal would be. He's getting much better about it though as he settles in and knows he is safe. 

AJ has spent very little time in a home environment and will need some patience and basic training to help him understand how to adapt to home life. After being at our rescue for a few weeks, he did very well during a visit to our head of animal care's home. He got along very well with the other dogs in the home, really loved the kids, and didn't seem to mind the cats at all. It was a fun sleepover for all! We believe AJ would do really well with an active adopter who likes to go for hikes and walks to keep this guy engaged and burn off some of that infectious hound energy.

Does AJ sound like your next BFF?

animal.description:
Because we are all volunteers, Illinois Doberman Rescue Plus only considers approved applicants to meet our orphans in our foster homes. Please read our eligibility requirements and apply on our website: www.ildoberescue.com/adopt.  After an application is submitted, additional inquiries can email dobes@ildoberescue.com.

Mojo and Josie Jo are an 8-year-old pair that originally arrived to IDR+ from a shelter in Arkansas. They were recently adopted, but the elderly father later moved in, and he kept tripping over them, so they were reluctantly returned. This beautiful pair of littermates are stuck like glue, and hope to find a home to adopt them together. Mojo and Josie Jo love attention from their people. Both love to get their ears rubbed, and Mojo is learning to enjoy a good massage to help loosen his muscles. He came to us moving very stiffly, and being confined for his heartworm treatment didn’t help. He has since recovered from his treatment and both are ready to go! His mobility is greatly improving now with regular exercise and supplements. He is beginning to run around the yard and stretch his legs! Josie Jo is also on an inexpensive daily supplement to help control very common leaking. They both need to go out often to pee. 

Both dogs are a little shy about changes. They are learning to accept new things and gain more confidence every day, but they are pretty set in their ways. Introductions to new dogs make Josie Jo a little nervous, and Mojo does not seem to appreciate high-energy dogs. They are strongly bonded to each other, and while we will continue to take it slow, they would probably be best placed in a household where they were the only two dogs. If you need a reason to be limited to two dogs, they’re the perfect package deal! They have an unknown history with cats and are recommended for children 12 and over, who are respectful and laid back with large breed dogs. We are not requiring an obedience deposit for this pair; however, we are requiring a fence since they love to lounge around in the sun and take it easy. If you have space for this sweet pair of bonded seniors, it would be incredible to find them a retirement home together.  

The biographical information provided is correct to the best of our knowledge while the animal is in our care or includes what may have been provided by a previous owner. We strive to be honest and accurate, but animals can change their personalities and behavior when they settle into a new home. IDR+ makes no guarantees based on the information we observe and provide.

animal.description:
Because we are all volunteers, Illinois Doberman Rescue Plus only considers approved applicants to meet our orphans in our foster homes. Please read our eligibility requirements and apply on our website: www.ildoberescue.com/adopt.  After an application is submitted, additional inquiries can email dobes@ildoberescue.com.

Mojo and Josie Jo are an 8-year-old pair that originally arrived to IDR+ from a shelter in Arkansas. They were recently adopted, but the elderly father later moved in, and he kept tripping over them, so they were reluctantly returned. This beautiful pair of littermates are stuck like glue, and hope to find a home to adopt them together. Mojo and Josie Jo love attention from their people. Both love to get their ears rubbed, and Mojo is learning to enjoy a good massage to help loosen his muscles. He came to us moving very stiffly, and being confined for his heartworm treatment didn’t help. He has since recovered from his treatment and both are ready to go! His mobility is greatly improving now with regular exercise and supplements. He is beginning to run around the yard and stretch his legs! Josie Jo is also on an inexpensive daily supplement to help control very common leaking. They both need to go out often to pee.

Both dogs are a little shy about changes. They are learning to accept new things and gain more confidence every day, but they are pretty set in their ways. Introductions to new dogs make Josie Jo a little nervous, and Mojo does not seem to appreciate high-energy dogs. They are strongly bonded to each other, and while we will continue to take it slow, they would probably be best placed in a household where they were the only two dogs. If you need a reason to be limited to two dogs, they’re the perfect package deal! They have an unknown history with cats and are recommended for children 12 and over, who are respectful and laid back with large breed dogs. We are not requiring an obedience deposit for this pair; however, we are requiring a fence since they love to lounge around in the sun and take it easy. If you have space for this sweet pair of bonded seniors, it would be incredible to find them a retirement home together.

The biographical information provided is correct to the best of our knowledge while the animal is in our care or includes what may have been provided by a previous owner. We strive to be honest and accurate, but animals can change their personalities and behavior when they settle into a new home. IDR+ makes no guarantees based on the information we observe and provide.
animal.name: Mojo & Josie Jo (bonded pair)

animal.description:
OMG JUST LOOK AT MY HAPPY SMILE AND BE PREPARED TO FALL INSTANTLY IN LOVE.  Show me some patience and we can probably make this arrangement be one of the best things that ever happened to either of us.  Lisa has assured me that the right person is looking for me.

So here's the tail of my recent arrival at Blue Lion (the beginning of my life still hurts to think about) ... 

My person has moved and says they can't take me so here I am over at Blue Lion sitting in a big enclosure,  looking out across the prairie and wondering whatever possessed this person I loved and was willing to give my life to protect ... what made them want to move somewhere I can't go ... I’ll never understand it.

Ok, so onward and upward, I am a Central Asian Shepherd, 5 years old and serious as a heart attack about my job as the guardian of my person.  For this reason, it really is important that my new person have a love and understanding of guardian breeds and how we think and process info.  Love me and when we bond, I will give you unquestioning personal protection for every day of my life ... right to my last breath.

So, now you want to know if I like little dogs…  They are ok until they decide to run to me or past me, then they are pretty much a food group. Cats? You probably don’t want to take that chance. Did I mention that I have a tendency not to sugar coat my words?  Oh, maybe Lisa should move this up higher in my bio....  Lisa? 

Regarding my interaction with dogs my size and larger ... as long as they don't show aggression to me or my person,  I will tolerate their presence, but you can forget that whole play group/dog park concept.  My person and I don't need any group activities. 

I am good on leash and I am respectful of a 6' or higher fence.  I occasionally try to dig if you stick me outside in a yard alone when you leave. I mean, really, how am I supposed to guard the house against burglars? Are you more concerned with your tulips being stolen or do you want to prevent that big beautiful flat screen TV from exiting the building? If you don’t get that concept, you and I are probably not a good match. 

Other stuff…I’m spayed, up to date on vaccinations and microchipped. 

Please seriously consider whether you want to make a lifetime commitment to a girl like me and know that I will keep you safe for the rest of my life.  Look over Lisa's adoption application and consider whether you have it takes to be a guardian's guardian.  We are a pretty selective group and Lisa is going to be very picky.

animal.description:
Bennie is an adorable & friendly senior Beagle mix who is 8+ years old and weighs 51 lbs.  Here's what his foster mom has to say about this charming little dude ...

Are you looking for a constant companion?  This 8+ year old gentleman is the dog for you!  Bennie is truly one fantastic dog!  In addition to being housebroken and crate-trained, he is calm, well-mannered, and adapts well to a routine.  He follows you from room to room, spot to spot.  He enjoys sitting on the couch with you, and in the bed if you'll let him.  He loves to go for walks, but hold on tight because when his beagle nose catches the scent of a woodland creature, he is on it!  He also has a tendency to bark at passing cars. Bennie enjoys plush squeak toys, but expect them to end up in small pieces.  He also enjoys antlers, they last much longer.  Bennie is good in the bath, and the car, but likes to be up front with you unless you have a car gate.  He gets along well people & dogs (he's a little too interested in cats for his own good) and is looking for a family that is home most of the time, or able to take him with them.  He also feels most comfortable being left at home with a canine companion .  Pictures do not do this short stack justice, and when he puts his head between his paws and looks up at you with his big brown eyes, you'll feel so lucky to call him yours!

Bennie has just finished heartworm treatment so he is slowly increasing his activity level. He is neutered, fully vaccinated & microchipped.

For more information about Bennie, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt sweet Bennie, please submit an application for him at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
This is Jericho and Annie. They are a bonded senior pair (6 -7 years old) not only are they siblings, but they also had a litter of puppies together before they came to our rescue. Both dogs lived on a chain their entire lives and their frail bodies and scars tell a story of their own. They both came into our rescue after their owner and all their fur friends passed away. We were very lucky to find a foster home that allowed them to stay together through heart worm treatment and they really enjoyed their female lab, but now it's time for them to find a home of their own. We know it will not be easy, but these dogs are gentle, well mannered and not too big. We are hopeful that there is an older person or family out there who needs them just as much as these kids need you. Our normal adoption fee is $200 per dog, we are considering Jericho and Annie an inseparable pair which means they will be $200 total. They absolutely must stay together. NO CATS. 
THEY LOVE CHILDREN! very gentle and would make great support pets for young children. they are dog selective but seem to do better with females. heart worms are not contagious but do require that these 2 are on limited restriction in regards to exercise for the next 30 days as well as remain on heart worm prevention for the reminder of their life. Please help us show the world that it's possible to save 2 senior pits and find a good forever home even when all odds are against them. they are the most deserving of all and will not be high maintenance dogs at ALL.

animal.description:
Dallas is a STUNNING 2.5 year old Heeler Shepherd mix, weighing 65lbs.
If you're looking for an exuberant exercise buddy, Dallas is the perfect dog for you! Hes got a lot of energy to burn and craves vigorous daily activity. He is a solid distance runner (right now a consistent 9.5 min/mile pace) and loves long hikes and walks. When he's not being an athlete he spends most of his day napping on his back with his feet sticking straight up in the air like a goofball and quietly playing with his toys.

Dallas gets along with other big dogs and could likely play with them for hours. He's friendly with strangers and loves getting attention from them. Hes got a high prey drive and will try to chase small dogs, cats, or wildlife.

Dallas is fully housebroken and generally doesn't pull on the leash.
He knows his basic "sit", "paw", and "lay down" commands.
Hes a good eater, fetch player, and car ride buddy. He will come over and put his head on your lap when he wants pets. Belly rubs are his favorite. Sometimes he thinks he's a lap dog and wants to lay on top of you. Hes a large snugglebug that will make your every day perfect. He is intelligent, inquisitive, and always strives to be the best boy.

To adopt Dallas, please fill out an application at EHRdogs.org

animal.description:
Meet Maude! Maude had a rough start in life. She came to us from the Suwannee County hoarding case where over 100 dogs were found in uninhabitable conditions. Prior to her rescue, she did not have any positive experiences with people. She is extremely nervous and will need a patient person who is willing to give her all of the love and time she needs. Because of her nerves, Maude is considered a flight risk and her adopters must have a securely fenced backyard. Maude has lived with other dogs and cats and done well with them all. She finds comfort in the presence of other dogs and needs to live with a well adjusted, friendly dog to show her the way. She will occasionally wrestle with the other dog in her foster home and play with her crinkly chicken toy. Maude also enjoys chewing on her no-hide bones. Her favorite place to be is curled up in a ball on her foster mom's bed- she looks like a little snowball! Although she isn't yet comfortable with direct attention from people she likes to be around people and gets nervous when she cannot see them. Due to this, we think she would do best with a person who stays home most of the time. When left alone, she may be destructive. She is working on establishing the crate as a safe space to prevent her destructive response. To work on her socialization, Maude completes a series of enrichment games, exposure walks, and hand lure sessions with peanut butter every day. Due to her nervous nature, Maude is looking for a quiet home with calm energy and no kids. 
REQUIREMENTS: No kids, fenced backyard, few hours spent alone, and another friendly dog must live in the home

Please visit our website at faithfulfriendsrescue.org/adoptable-pets if you are interested in adopting.

I am a mixed breed dog. This means I don't have a specific recognizable breed. The rescue uses the following guide which are guesses based on my current size and age for how big I will be when full grown: Mixed Breed (small) up to 25 pounds - Mixed Breed (medium) between 25-45 pounds - Mixed Breed (large) more than 50 pounds. For more information on, please visit the website https://faithfulfriendsrescue.org/adoptable-pets.

We are setting up adoptions with approved adopters on an appointment basis. We are no longer hosting adoption events at PetSmart until further notice. We are not arranging meet and greets; but appointments to finalize adoptions to limit exposure for all. Our adoptions come with a one week trial period in which if things are not working out, we will refund your adoption fee if you decide to return your newly adopted Faithful Friend. Our adoptions must be done in person and we do not arrange transport to adopters. Our adoption fees vary and we are only able to accept payments by card* at this time but include spay/neuter, heartworm test (dogs), FeLV/FIV test (cats), age appropriate vaccines and deworming, flea, tick and heartworm medication and microchip.

animal.description:
Why Choose Me?

*$150 in sponsorship funds available to rescue group!*

Update 10/7: Chance enjoyed a doggie-day-out at Sandy Creek Park and had the best time. Playing fetch and being with a friend was so much fun! An afternoon away from the pound gave Chance an opportunity to show what a great dog he really is. He rode well in the car, practiced good manners, and didn’t bark when other dogs walked by his play yard. He was just curious and interested in what they were doing. Chance was so good, he got to enjoy some ice cream before going back to the pound. What a great day!

Update 9/21: I had so much fun with Chance today! He was thrilled to have someone to play with and even happier that I had treats. I used his love for treats to begin working with him on playing fetch. At first, he’d chase a toy and then run with it, but eventually he learned that if he’d bring it back to me, he’d earn a treat. What a great student! Chance is a smart dog, and I bet he could learn other tricks with patience and treats. He already knows how to sit for them. He’s a good boy who just needs someone to take him home and give him a chance!

Chance may look like a tough guy, but he’s inside he’s a scared pup still trying to figure out what’s expected of him. Because he was uncertain how to act when he got to the shelter, he spent some time in the back settling into the shelter routine before he was evaluated and, ultimately, moved to the front. 

The trainer who evaluated him says he’s very responsive to voice corrections (something I saw as well–when he was annoyed with the youngsters in the pen next to him, I was able to call him off easily) but because of his uncertainty he’s a better fit with older children and adults than with small kids. He also has a prey drive so he should not be placed with cats. He’s looking for a home that will boost his confidence and show him the world is a friendly place!

To learn more about Chance or to meet him, please call the shelter at 706-613-3540.

You can read more about this dog and check out additional photos here: https://athenspets.net/Adoptables/53810-chance/ OR check out our urgent dogs (http://tinyurl.com/Athenspets-FB-URGENT-Dogs) on Facebook!

This dog is currently at Athens-Clarke County Animal Control, located at 125 Buddy Christian Way, Athens, GA. For the most timely information on hours, location, availability and how to adopt, call the shelter any day from 10am-4pm at 706-613-3540 or go to https://www.athensclarkecounty.com/133/Animal-Control.
