!!! AVAILABLE for Adoption from Foster Care !!! 


REX A-64982 


Personality: Here's a medium dog that would love to just cuddle up with you for a movie marathon! Rex loves taking walks around the neighborhood- even five year olds have to keep their body in shape! He's shy at first, but it only takes a tiny bit of effort, a good home, and a few treats, for him to show how loving he can be! 

Intake Type: Stray 

Weight: 52 lbs 

Medical Observations:
(2/21) Patient appears healthy, asides from being underweight and having a low grade heart murmur. Heart murmur does not preclude surgery at the shelter, however recommend adoption with medical waiver indicating heart murmur presence. 

Behavior Observations:
(3/6) Volunteer Note -- Leash biting onsite. He doesn't go up the leash but does do that hard tug as he flips his head back and forth. Once we got moving, he dropped the leash and began walking. For the remainder of our walk he would periodically grab the leash and begin to leash bite, before dropping it voluntarily and continuing to walk. He did this several times, the episodes only lasted 10-15 seconds. So he's not a consistent leash biter but when he is doing it, he tugs hard and puts his weight into it. Returning to kennel he became a bit reactive to passing dogs as we walked through the kennels. No issues returning to kennel.
(2/28) Short Term foster -- Rex is a very sweet and gentle dog. He was shy at first, but showed improvement each day by coming out of his shell when he was with me.
(2/21) Lifesaving -- Slight hesitation but overall easy to loop. Distracted going back in but no real issues. Pulls on leash and would do best harnessed, but manageable if not. Aroused but allows all over handling. Will come to handler for more pets when stopped. Engages in tag/chase games followed by LOTS of zoomies! Will jump on handler gently. No interest in toys at this time. Suggested Running Team. Evaluated Gold.
(2/21) Per Vet Staff -- Friendly
(2/18) Per Finder -- Friendly, well mannered, sweet 


This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. This animal is not onsite. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact foster@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster.

!!! AVAILABLE for Adoption from Foster Care !!! 


GLINDA - A#42130953 

Foster's Email: frankferra@gmail.com 


Pictures and Video:
Glinda in foster care - https://photos.app.goo.gl/k5rWxZSiyvsoyEHZ7 

Dog meet: 
https://youtu.be/u7EzA47nZsQ 

Personality: Glinda is a sweet and gentle soul. She is approximately 7 years old with a lot puppy energy left in her and would thrive in a household that could give her lots of attention. She loves to be goofy in the yard entertaining herself with the ball, rag doll, or bone and adores to cuddle on the couch with you to watch a movie or read a book. Did I mention she enjoys to give kisses in the most gentle manner? And of course, those belly rubs....what dog doesn't enjoy those? 

Glinda has some quirks, like us all. I do notice she has a huge prey drive...which means she chases birds that happen to be flying by (yes, even 300 yards in the sky, lol), squirrels, and she is not a fan of moving cars. Although, during the past few walks, she seems to be getting desensitized....which is great! She does not enjoy car rides. We plan to experiment with soft crates in the car to see how she reacts to them. 

Glinda is crate trained and obeys some commands. Her recall is actually pretty good too. She will eat any food you give her - she is not picky at all! She recently had bloodwork and a urine analysis which both came back clean. She is currently on Heartguard and Simparica (flea & tick). She is up to date on all her shots. If it were not for our resident dog being a bit too territorial, we would have kept Glinda. If you have any questions about Glinda, feel free to email me directly at frankferra@gmail.com. 

Intake Type: (7/5) Stray 

Weight: 55 lbs

Rosie is a sweet girl that was thrown away like trash in a rural part of the county without animal control. She was completely bald when we first got her and terribly underweight. Now though, Rosie has blossomed into the beautiful girl we knew she was. Her hair is back, and her personality is really shining through- and it’s a wonderful one. Rosie is happy about life, ready to play, loves to party and play with her tennis balls. Rosie is a great girl that would make an excellent family companion.

animal.description:
Two is better than one...especially in this case!

Tootsie and Tansey are bonded, female, chihuahua mix sisters. They are about 1 to1.5 years old and have been together since birth. They are looking for their new furever home together to continue their story. Although timid at first, they are very sweet and affectionate when they feel comfortable. All these sisters are looking for is to be snuggled and loved! Tootsie even has a little heart shape on her side;  if that doesn’t show how loving she is, we don't know what will!

Tootsie and Tansey were surrendered by their owner who wasn’t able to provide them a safe, loving living environment. They may have had a rough start, with their previous owner not treating them well BUT since being at STARS they have been showered with love and affection. Will you continue to show these two, sweet sisters the love they deserve?

Click on www.starsrescue.org to complete an application to be pre-approved to adopt this pup. As you can imagine, we get a lot of interest in our rescues and kindly ask that you are patient with us while we review applications as it may take a few days.We will contact you regarding your application, during which you can ask more questions about this specific pup. If pre-approved we will coordinate a date for meet and greet.

Our adoption fee is $500 each. This includes spay/neuter, microchipping, deworming, and all age-appropriate vaccinations.

animal.description:
Hi We're DAISY & LUCA!!  We're a sister (red)/brother (brindle/white) pair of 2 yr Dachshund/Pitbull Mixes. Yes believe it or not.. our mommy was a pitbull and daddy was a dachshund! We're about 26 lbs each of PURE SUGAR & SPICE!!  We're sweet and friendly, happy go lucky and fun loving clowns!.  We're very playful, active & love to wrestle with each other and do zoomies in the yard. We're not walked so much because we have the yard so we would definitely need leash training.. but we are crate trained and house trained. We are good with the dogs that we live with but have not met alot of other dogs outside of our pack, so we bark at new dogs and would need "socialization" training. We do like to bark when we hear noises or folks knocking at the door or if begging for treats!!. We don't like cats so NO CATS for us!. We are fine with kids as long as they are older ages 10 yrs+. We are too strong for younger kids and would definitely knock them over. Our ideal home would be with someone/couple or family (with older kids) that have a fenced in yard (apt in city is NOT good for us) and is active i.e runner, biker, hiker, rollerblader .. because we are very active dogs and need hoomans that can keep up with us and are willing to give us the daily structured exercise and discipline we need. We're still young and very quick to learn, eager to please and are sure to give you lots of "sh*ts & giggles"! We're a dynamic duo and are BFFs and cannot be split up!! If you want a pair of Silly, Happy Goofballs... pls come meet us today!

For more info/application - pls email: INFO@TAILSOFLOVERESCUE.ORG

animal.description: Roscoe was brought to the Galveston shelter by his owner who asked to have him euthanized.  Thankfully, the shelter saw how much life Roscoe still has in him and reached out to see if a rescue would take him, which we did.  He was flown to us in Dallas, TX via pilots n paws.  Unfortunately, Roscoe had been SEVERELY neglected for a long time.  Something happened to him a long time ago and medical intervention was not sought in time.  Now Roscoe is paralyzed forever.  When we got him, he was in AWFUL shape.  Filthy...  he’d been laying in his own feces and urine for a LONG time.  He had urine burns all over his legs and belly and oozing sores, his nails were so long and his teeth were in dreadful shape, we took him to a neurologist who found that he can’t move or feel his right leg, tail or the outside digits and flexor muscles of his left pelvic limb.  He can feel the inside digits.  He may even have some voluntary movement of the flexors of his hip.  However, because he can’t bear weight effectively in the limb, he's unable to use it to walk on three legs.  There are numerous possible causes of his paralysis.  Regardless of the underlying cause, because of the severity of his spinal cord disease (he can’t feel his feet) as well as the chronicity, there is no treatment for any neurologic improvement.  He will remain a paralyzed dog for the rest of his life.  The good news is that Roscoe has a wheelchair, which he's a natural at using.  While we can’t know his long-term prognosis for sure, it’s entirely possible that Roscoe will live for many more years as a happy handicapped dog.  He’s full of energy, has a lot of great spirit and a gregarious nature.  Roscoe doesn’t have bladder or bowel control so his bladder needs to be expressed a few times/day.  It’s not difficult, in return for caring for him, he will reward you with SO much love and devotion and make you smile, he loves to go on walks and get attention from everyone, and he just wants to be part of the action.  He’s feisty, affectionate, cheerful, playful, sensitive, gentle, intelligent, active, alert, faithful, and incredibly sweet.  Please give Roscoe the loving forever home he deserves.  You can meet him at the Plano PetSmart, 6204 West Park Boulevard, Saturdays and Sundays from 1-5.  You can make a donation on our website, https://www.poochsavers.com/donate/, thank you and PS, Roscoe’s adoption fee is reduced thanks to a grant from The Petfinder Foundation

animal.description:
Hi!  I’m Bubba! I’m an almost 5-year old Rottweiler mix.  At around 65 lbs, I’ve been called the perfect size! My friends tell me I’m handsome.  Do you think so?

I’m not sure where I got my name. Maybe I’m named after Bubba Watson? Although, I don’t golf. Or Bubba Wallace? But, like most dogs, I can’t drive.  Or Bubba Starling? I like to play ball, but my batting skills are lacking without opposable thumbs. Or Bubba Gump? But I don’t know much about the shrimping business. Maybe I could be called Bubba-licious? Frankly, I just want you to call me yours!

I don’t want to toot my own horn, but I’m a pretty sweet guy. I seem to love all people, big and small. And I’m so eager to please!  I want to be your one and only dog, but I promise, I’m all you need!  I have so much love to give all humans.

On a perfect day, I would spend some time running, rolling in the grass, lounging in the grass, and sitting for some yummy treats. I really like cheese. That stuff is good! (Unless you want to get really fancy with rotisserie chicken. I won’t complain!)  My nub tail really wiggles so fast when I get to do those things. It also wags so fast if you talk silly to me. Humans are so funny with their silly talk, but I love it. I also love to play with stuffies and rope toys—I run and place them where I think they belong in the yard.

Between you and me, I’ve been bounced around quite a bit, so I really want my next home to be my forever. That’s what I dream about at night. And well, frankly, also during the day! (We dogs can take some naps you know!) Are you my dream come true?

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 for more info on Bubba. He's neutered and up to date on vaccines and is hanging out with us in the Kansas City metro. But transport is available to the right home.


INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET? Fill out an Adoption Application now! Appointments can also be made to meet a pet by calling us at 913-671-PETS (913-671-7387).  

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
Prior to adoption, our animals are: 
**Tested for diseases 
**Vaccinated 
**Spayed/neutered 
**Microchipped 

NO COST adoptions with an encouraged donation are accepted. 

The Pet Connection also offers adopters a FREE veterinary examination and a medical care support plan for 60 days after adoption, as well as lifetime behavioral training, safe sanctuary for pets returned in emergency situations, extensive assistance with lost and found pets, and other expert pet services in a variety of areas, including pet selection, behavioral issues, general training, nutrition, and transition to adoptive homes.

Please visit our website at www.thepetconnection.org for more information about The Pet Connection and for a full listing of our available pets, 

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 if you can foster, adopt, or sponsor a special needs dog or cat! 

The Pet Connection is a membership organization operating a no-kill adoption center in Shawnee Mission, Kansas.

animal.description:
Rufus T. is a handsome, affectionate 10-year-old male German Shepherd Dog (GSD) who was left at a shelter in Southern California because his family felt that they could no longer provide care for him. Rufus is suffering from severe hip dysplasia and spondylosis. As a result, Rufus loses control of his hind legs when walking or running. This is particularly true when he is excited. He is an enthusiastic dog who loves people and is very active despite his disability. He is well mannered, loves attention and is very food motivated. TSGSR brought Rufus into their care and he is quickly adapting to his new surroundings. Rufus appears to have been very well loved. He is housetrained, walks on leash and gets along with other dogs.

Rufus T. Summary:
- Rufus is a Male, 10 yrs old, weighs 81 lbs, current on shots excluding rabies
- Good with Adults, dogs, and travel in the car

Rufus is a wonderful, sweet dog who really wants to engage his human! He has received care for his ears and skin and will be visiting the TSGSR veterinarian for additional medical evaluation to assess the damage to his hips. The vet determined that his hip issues will continue to progress. Rufus is very interested in everything around him and has adapted to his disability. He accepts help getting into cars, rides well in the car and makes great eye contact . He is in need of a loving home with a family that can love him despite his disability.

Rufus passed a set of behavior tests before being accepted into the TSGSR. The tests are not intended to assess how smart the dog is but are important for TSGSR to determine if the dog is expected to be safe in a family home. The tested behaviors check to see if the dog will guard or protect food or toys from people, will tolerate handling all over its body (including ears, nose, lips to check teeth, lifting paws, belly, back, and gently pulling the tail) and the ability to get along with other well behaved dogs. Rufus remained calm during all of these tests and showed no aggressive tendencies. 

Please join us in welcoming sweet Rufus to TSGSR! Rufus is a hospice/adopt dog because of his progressing hip issues.

What's Next for Rufus T.:
Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR) will continue to see that Rufus is well cared for and receives all medical care needed for his well being while in our care. In addition, TSGSR is beginning a search for an adoptive home that will care for him for the rest of his life. Rufus will come to his new home with a supply of food, a cushy pad if wanted, and other goodies such as toys. 

TSGSR will provide limited coverge of Rufus' medical expenses for the rest of his life.

If you want to learn more about him, or are possibly interested in providing an adoptive or foster home, please send us a message by clicking on the "Ask About Me" button. We will often get feedback or "updates" from a dog's foster home and as any updates become available they will be included here.

If you are reading about Rufus on Petfinder.com sometimes an available YouTube video is not listed. If this occurs you can still view the video by pasting its URL into a new browser window or tab.
Available Video URL(s): https://youtu.be/XjI_EFoiDCg


Saving one dog wont change the world. It will change the world for that one dog.
animal.name: Rufus T

animal.description:
Looking for a cuddle buddy?? Please let Loki love you! He is looking for someone to love him as much as he will love you. He is looking for someone patient and willing to work with him and his new hip! Loki is almost fully recovered from a hip surgery to help an old fracture from before moving to Colorado. He is stronger everyday! He is one handsome boy and he sure wants you to know it! He is a gentle, playful guy who will steal your heart with his good nature, loving demeanor, and constant cuddling. He is great with other dogs and will mimic their playstyle and energy level! Ask his foster sister, she loves playing with him, but she loves napping with him even more! What could be better?! He is still working on his leash manners, its hard when he also has to practice social distancing! 

Loki is house trained, great on a leash and loves his crate. He is still having a lot of new experiences, so taking things slow is a must. He isn't perfect at commands, but will do anything to please you. A perfect addition to a kind and patient family looking for a pup to smother them with love, kisses, and ALL the cuddles.

*Homeownership required!

	Spay/Neuter

animal.description: Geri is an adorable pup that adores her humans. Her sweet demeanor and laid back couch potato attitude make her a great snuggle bug. She can't wait to start lounging with her humans! This smart girl is house trained and will happily sit at the door waiting to be let outside to do her business. In her foster home she's free to roam doing great without a crate. Although she doesn't know a lot of commands, she's happy to learn with a little patience. When it comes to others, Geri has a total soft spot for her people. She prefers to be the only animal friend in the home, though. Her people are her world and she loves to hop on the couch to cuddle with you, if you invite her to join. Her walks are also dear to her...she'll talk to you and let you know if you've forgotten about one. The vocalness will crack you up. Geri's ideal home would be quiet and low traffic, where she's the center of your animal world. Her docile and loving attitude are endearing and she deserves a home that needs a Netflix buddy. Come meet her!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Online Adoption Application 
A sweet boy looking for a patient owner and doggy siblingOzzy is a very sweet boy who is looking for a patient owner who is willing to help him become the dog we know he can be.He was abandoned on a farm when he was young and had very little human interaction before he was rescued. He has spent the last few months in his foster home learning how to be a real dog! Despite having spent most of his life outside, he has learned that he loves being an inside dog. Ozzy absolutely loves playing with his doggy friends (although he needs some time to get to know them so he's comfortable) and is learning that toys are pretty great. He is still learning how to trust humans, but has come a very long way since he came to his foster home. He gets nervous and tries to hide when he sees hands reaching for him but he loves being petted when he is in a place where he feels comfortable.
Ozzy has made good progress on leash training, but is still a little nervoys on a leash. He would like to have a fenced yard. We would prefer that he go to a home with another dog so he can learn from them and they can help reinforce that humans are good. Ozzy is mostly housetrained and crate trained (although he has not been staying in a crate lately in his foster home). He would do best in a home with no young children. He would probably spend most of his time trying to hide from them since they won't know to take it slow with him.Ozzy is not a super 'cuddly' dog, but he enjoys spending time around his foster parents and will make a wonderful companion for the right family.

animal.description:
Cammie is 3 years and 60lbs. She came to us on 8/22 from a neighboring county pound.

My name is Cammie, I'm only 3 years old, but I've already lived a lifetime. I am heartworm positive and a tripod due to severe arthritis from an old untreated injury. I won't go into details about my life so far, but I will share some highlights. I wandered my neighborhood as a stray until they finally took me to my local pound. I was scared and confused, so I made sure I scared everyone away from my kennel while I gathered my thoughts. One of the ladies from FCHS wouldnt leave me alone though and one day she let me come out. I was so excited, I wasnt sure where to go first, but one of my legs hurt so I picked it up to keep it from slowing me down. Even though i was happy to be out of my kennel, she still made me a little uncomfortable and i let her know. She brought me back with her and now I not only have a love for her, but several of the employees at FCHS. I've realized not all people are bad and the same goes for dogs too, but I'm still very uncomfortable at first. I'm sure many of you have seen me barking and growling in my kennels. That's my fear talking, so I need someone willing to turn away from me and let me interact with them before they interact with me. I need someone who understands that I will become more and more loving as time goes on. I just want to be with you, go for walks, lay in your lap, chase a ball that I may or may not bring back. There are so many things for me to enjoy and I just need a confident person familiar with my dog breed to help me do just that. I love car rides, just make sure I'm strapped in or I may want to be in your lap. I also bark at people when in the car and may always bark at people when behind a barrier because I'm so uncertain. I dont want that to stop you from coming to see me, I know it's something I need to work on, and I'm hoping you can help me do just that. I have shown an interest in playing with dogs and met a few, but I'm a bit of a noisy player, so I'm trying to get more comfortable here so I can make a friend or two confidently. My amputation has also stopped me from making a friend so far, because I have to let it heal. Life is hard, but companionship makes it better. Want to be my companion? I cant wait to be yours.

Inquiries: adoptions@plannedpethoodrockymount.com
Adoption Application Link: https://www.plannedpethoodrockymount.com/adoptions

Click here to view our general adoption fees. Our adoption fees help to provide a portion of the care that we provide our animals.

Prior to adoption, all of our animals are altered, vaccinated, microchipped, tested for heartworm (dogs), and placed on a monthly preventative, in addition to other necessary treatments.

Adoption Center Hours:
Tuesday - Friday:: 12-6p.m.
Saturday:: 11-4p.m.

At FCHS, we commit to our animals; for this reason, all of our animals have a lifetime commitment from us. If an adoption does not work out, for any reason, we ask that all FCHS animals be returned to our facility.

animal.description:
Adoption Fee: $400
Fostered in Longview, Texas
Age: 5 years
Weight: 4.7 lbs.

9/28/20 - Daisy Lynn is settling in to her foster home quit nicely.  She has graduated to the big bed with her humans and she LOVES it.   She is eating good and we are pleased as she needs to gain a little.  She will have accidents sometimes, but will always go when brought outside.  When her foster mom has to go out, she will leave her in an area with a potty pad and she seems to find it and use it.  Smarty pants!  She rides ok, but does want to be near her person.  We were letting her get comfortable, but will be setting up her vet appointment for her necessary shots, etc.

9/18/20 - Daisy Lynn loves people.  She loves to be held and loved on and kissed.  She gets attached to her people/person very fast.  She is eating very good.  She does bump into things, but we feel that once settled and learns her way of a house, it will get much better.  Even though she is good around other dogs, since she is blind, she does not like sniffs of the butt or another dog coming up to her quickly.  For now, and this could change with time, we think she would be best in a home with laid back senior dogs, or possibly just cats, or an only dog.  Just somewhere that isn't too active.  As we learn more, we will update.

9/16/20 - Daisy Lynn and her foster mom left the Veterinary Eye Institute in Dallas, Tx around 8:30.  We will be getting a formal report tomorrow and will be in a better position to give a more accurate update, but the short summary is that Daisy Lynn's right eye had an ulcer that ruptured previously.  It has already tried to protect/heal itself and scarred over.  She is not squinting, blinking or trying to avoid light, so they do not believe this eye is uncomfortable at this point.

Her left eye, the one that we referred to as bulging, has a mature cataract and glaucoma.  The doctor said that her pressure in that eye is lower than normal, so there is no scare there of doggy migraines or pain.   

At this point, we can discontinue the eye medicine that was originally prescribed for the other group and our doctor is starting her on Ketorolac to be administered to both eyes twice daily just to help with any inflammation.

There isn't a surgery that will help her, she is totally blind in both eyes, but she isn't in any pain and he feels she is quite used to her situation.  We are sure that at some point both eyes truly hurt her and that is sad to think about, so we will focus on the present and just give her all the love and attention she can stand.  We had hoped that there would be something that could help her see, but at least she isn't in pain and is probably already used to her blindness.

We will update personality after we have had about a week to see her true colors come out.  Thank you to everyone who prayed and everyone who donated.  She won't arrive home until about 10:30 tonight and then will be ready to curl up for a long night's sleep.  
 
9/16/20 - Daisy Lynn was picked up stray and brought to a shelter in Shreveport, Louisiana.  They knew right away that she needed to be out of the shelter and in a rescue group, so they reached out Carley's Angels, Senior Sanctuary and Hospice who immediately picked her up.  They got her cleaned up and then could really tell the extent of her eye problems.  She has an ulcerated right eye and her left eye is bulging.  Knowing that they would not be able to get the medical attention this little girl needed, they quickly reached out to Yorkie Haven Rescue and one of our foster homes left almost as soon as she got the call.  We are in the process of getting the vet in Shreveport to send over a referral to the eye specialist in Plano, Tx and schedule an appointment as soon as we can get it.

We are not sure exactly what we are going to be looking at in terms of if she can have surgery and save 1 or both of her eyes or if she is even a candidate, but we do know that we have to do everything we can to give this young girl the comfort and eyes she should have.  The ones she had before whatever happened to them took place.

We do not know much about her currently in terms of personality right now since foster mom just picked her up tonight, but as soon as she is more comfortable and we can access her, we will update.  Right now, all we are focusing on is getting this appointment set and seeing if we can shed new light on this baby's eyes.  

We don't even have an estimate right now, but donations would be greatly appreciated.  We know that they way things are right now, not everyone can donate, but please pray for Daisy Lynn as prayers are just as important.

Thank you.
